<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Often forgotten President Fillmore remembered by home town  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SUMMERHILL, N.Y. (AP) - Few may remember the nation's 13th
president, but his hometown area was giddy this weekend in
celebrating the 200th year of Millard Fillmore's birth and the
150th year since his inauguration.
</P>
<P>
   Fillmore's delayed birthday celebration - the date is Jan. 7,
1800 - and the commemoration of his inauguration was combined with
the opening of a new town hall and community center.
</P>
<P>
   State Assemblyman Gary Finch described Fillmore, president from
1850-53, as often misunderstood. The celebration 5 miles east of
where Fillmore was born in a log cabin in Locke, about 70 miles
southeast of Rochester, tried to change that for some. Finch said
that led to underrating Fillmore's role in history. He said
Fillmore was a great negotiator and statesman whose administration
delayed the Civil War for 10 years while the North was able to
build railroads and strengthen its defenses.
</P>
<P>
   ''His life was a tribute to his sterling character,'' the
Republican said, according to The Citizen of Auburn.
</P>
<P>
   ''I won't be giving a history lesson, but for many reasons I
wish he was president now,'' said Cayuga County Sheriff Peter
Pickney.
</P>
<P>
   Historical presentations were given by Robert Scarry, author and
historian, whose book on the long-lost Fillmore papers will be
available in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   The accomplishments of the former vice president (under Zachary
Taylor, 1849-1850) include the Compromise of 1850, the expansion of
the Erie Canal, and a role in founding the city of Buffalo.
Fillmore also signed the Fugitive Slave Act and helped open trade
with Japan while fighting to close debtors' prisons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
