<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Mon, July 10, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Colombian President Outlaws Genocide
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- In a hard-fought victory for human rights activists,
President Andres Pastrana on Monday signed a law that officially outlaws
genocide and forced disappearances. The law put the crimes on the books, sets
sentences as high as 45 years and creates a commission to investigate the fate
of an estimated 3,000 missing people. Pastrana said that by signing the law he
had once vetoed, he was paying homage to the ''the spirit of so many who
suffered and the families who have searched desperately for their loved ones.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bank Workers Strike in S. Korea
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- After failing to obtain government guarantees for
their job security, tens of thousands of bank workers went on strike Tuesday.
The union is concerned the government's plans to restructure the industry would
spur bank mergers and lead to layoffs. The initial impact appeared limited, as
banks opened using non-union employees or union members who opposed the walkout.
Last-minute efforts to prevent the strike ended after bank union leaders walked
out of talks with government officials which lasted 6&AMP;frac12; hours.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Barak Leaves for Camp David Summit
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Prime Minister Ehud Barak on Monday headed to the U.S.
summit meeting on the Middle East, after narrowly surviving a no-confidence
vote. ''The government did not fall and I am continuing onward to Camp David,''
a grim Barak said, minutes after the opposition Likud party failed to muster the
necessary 61 votes in parliament to topple his government. The no-confidence
motion gathered 54 votes to 52 for Barak.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Fla. Smokers Seek Up to $196 Billion
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- Smokers in a Florida class-action trial asked a jury Monday for
a record $196 billion to punish the tobacco industry. ''Never have so few caused
so much harm to so many for so long, and the day of reckoning has arrived,''
said attorney Stanley Rosenblatt as closing arguments began in the two-year case
involving up to 700,000 sick Florida smokers. It could be the gravest legal
threat ever to the five biggest U.S. cigarette makers.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Wants Heating Oil Reserve
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton decided Monday to stockpile 2 million
barrels of heating oil in the Northeast as refineries concentrate on pumping out
as much gasoline as possible. He directed Energy Secretary Bill Richardson to
trade oil from the government's Strategic Petroleum Reserve for refined heating
oil that will be put into Northeast storage tanks. The goal is to have the fuel
in place within 90 days.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore Opposes Bush on Missiles
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW BRITAIN, Conn. (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore said Monday the failure of
a test for a national missile defense system does not mean the idea is doomed,
and he criticized the version supported by GOP presidential foe George W. Bush
as ''more expensive and less likely to work.'' The Democratic presidential
contender, answering online questions -- using The Washington Post's Web site,
said Bush's proposal is ''calculated to destroy arms control agreements with
Russia.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AT&AMP;T Says It's Being Cheated
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- AT&AMP;T accused Verizon Communications Monday of illegally
steering New York customers who call for local phone service to its own long
distance service. AT&AMP;T said Verizon, formerly Bell Atlantic, has violated
regulations by failing to have ''marketing neutrality'' in selling long distance
service to its customers. AT&AMP;T has asked the Federal Communications Commission
to force Verizon to pay damages, and stop Verizon from providing long distance
service in New York.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Slip in Early Trading
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks fell moderately Tuesday morning, pushed down by an
a slide in technology stocks on Wall Street. The dollar was higher against the
yen. The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei shed 60.67 points, or 0.35 percent, to
17,512.01 at the end of the morning session. On Monday, the average closed up
174.44 points, or 1.00 percent. On the stock market, the Nikkei index moved
lower during morning trading after the technology-heavy Nasdaq fell 42.91 points
to 3,980.29 at Monday's close in New York. The Dow Jones rose 10.60 points to
end at 10,646.58 on Monday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Sosa Wins Home Run Derby
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- Slammin' Sammy Sosa ended Ken Griffey Jr.'s two-year reign as
Home Run Derby champion, hitting the longest, loudest and largest number of
shots at Turner Field on Monday night. Sosa beat Griffey 9-2 in the finals and
hit 26 overall, including a pair of 508-foot shots -- one to the 755 Club in the
left-field upper deck and one that came to rest atop the second green batter's
backdrop in straightaway center, below the scoreboard.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by MARIA CODER
</SUBHEAD>
</TEXT>
