<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Despite higher prices, some happily use full-serve stations  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CAMP HILL, Pa. (AP) - There was once a time when it was an
unusual for gas stations to insist you pump your own fuel. These
days, full service is the novelty.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a service people don't get anymore,'' said Lester
Whitesell, who manages the full-service Keystone Super Service near
the Harrisburg suburb of Camp Hill. ''Most are pleasantly surprised
we offer it.''
</P>
<P>
   The extra cost is worth it to a niche market.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have a lot of senior citizens and disabled customers from
nearby Messiah Village and Bethany Village,'' Whitesell said. ''We
pump gas, check oil, clean the windshield, fill the tires and do
whatever they ask.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray Dormer of Middletown, a paraplegic who uses a wheelchair and
drives a van, said he considers a full-service gas station a
necessity, not a luxury.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have a lift in my van, but it's a pain to get in my
wheelchair, get out, pump gas and get back in,'' Dormer said. ''So
I just pull up, roll down the window and get the gas pumped. It
costs a little more, $1.60 a gallon, but it's worth it. My (van's)
windows get cleaned and my oil gets checked, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Dormer usually gets his tank filled at Elwood's Sunoco Service
in Middletown, which charges only a few cents more per gallon for
full service. But even at stations where the price of full-service
gas has soared above $2 a gallon, there hasn't been a drop in
demand for full service.
</P>
<P>
   ''Consumers today prefer self service because of the convenience
and speed,'' said David Callahan, executive director of the
Associated Petroleum Industries of Pennsylvania. ''But a small
segment of the population needs or wants full-serve stations. So
they will stay.''
</P>
<P>
   Only New Jersey and Oregon require all gas stations to offer
full service, Callahan said. The rest of the nation offers both.
The association does not track the number of full- and self-serve
stations, Callahan said.
</P>
<P>
   But the customers who appreciate full-service stations go beyond
the elderly and disabled.
</P>
<P>
   Brandi Alfaro, 21, of Harrisburg uses a full-service station
''to get things checked under the hood.'' She smiled as attendant
Rick Wissler pumped gas, checked her car's fluids and added a quart
of oil.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Miller, owner of Miller's Ultra Service Center in
Harrisburg, where Alfaro gets gas, said a quarter of his customers
choose full service.
</P>
<P>
   ''Full-service customers may not like to pump gasoline or have
the smell of it on their hands,'' he said. ''They also want us to
wash their windshield, check their tire pressure and check their
oil, transmission fluid, power-steering fluid and antifreeze
levels. They're happy with our service, but not with gas prices.''
</P>
<P>
   That's true at Miller's gas station even though Miller charges a
premium for full service. Alfaro bypasses Miller's self-service,
where regular unleaded gasoline sells for $1.62 a gallon, to pay
$2.04 a gallon for full service.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
