<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 00:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hotels briefed on what to expect  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL RUBINKAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) - A crummy hotel stay can really sour a
person's impression of a place.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, representatives of the hospitality industry
are fanning out across the region this week to brief hoteliers on
how to make the most of the upcoming Republican National
Convention.
</P>
<P>
   About 25 managers at the Philadelphia Marriott attended the
first workshop Monday. The Marriott is one of 95 hotels housing the
45,000 delegates, guests and journalists expected to attend the
convention from July 31 to Aug. 3.
</P>
<P>
   ''You are very important to this whole process and how people
feel about their stay in Philadelphia,'' said Karen Buchholz,
executive director of the Philadelphia 2000 host committee. ''This
is our time to shine.''
</P>
<P>
   A pleasant stay can be dependent on lots of little things. For
example, the delegates have a 10 a.m. session on the first morning
of the convention and must arrive much earlier to clear security.
So it might behoove hotel restaurant managers to serve breakfast a
little earlier than usual, said Philomena Petro, director of
convention services for the Philadelphia Convention and Visitor's
Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   The Marriott, which is connected to the Pennsylvania Convention
Center, has extensive experience hosting large gatherings. In a
sense, Monday's session was a refresher.
</P>
<P>
   The managers got a ''Hospitality Readiness Program'' packet that
contained tips for concierges, an address list for 30 of
Philadelphia's most famous landmarks and a matching game with 10
easy questions about the city. (Example: Find both the Liberty Bell
and Independence Hall. Answer: Between 5th and 6th streets on
Chestnut Street.) Petro suggested the quiz be distributed to all
hotel staffers, with a prize drawing for participants.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think that all 95 hotels are geared up for this. I don't
think this is really brand new for anyone. It's just larger in
scope,'' Buchholz said.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Hines, general manager of the Marriott, said the hotel
will have key managers on duty 24 hours a day during the four-day
convention.
</P>
<P>
   ''I personally am very excited for it and that's kind of out of
my nature,'' said Hines, who has been in the hotel business 24
years but never experienced a national political convention.
</P>
<P>
   The host committee has also asked each hotel to set up a welcome
desk decorated in red, white and blue, where delegates and
journalists can obtain information on the city or book a tour.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.gopconvention.com
</P>
<P>
   Host committee site: http://www.philadelphia2000.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
