<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 01:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Day 2 of U.S.-N.Korea Missile Talks  </HEADLINE>
By DEAN VISSER
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) -- U.S. and North Korean officials
entered a second day of talks Tuesday on Pyongyang's development
and export of missiles.
</P>
<P>
   The talks began Monday on an optimistic note, with the American
negotiator saying the United States was prepared to move toward
fundamentally improved relations with North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Einhorn, U.S. assistant secretary of state for
nonproliferation, greeted North Korean delegates with handshakes
and smiles as they arrived early Tuesday at the U.S. Embassy in
Kuala Lumpur, where Washington and Pyongyang have held several
meetings in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The North Korean delegation was led by Jang Chang Chon, head of
the country's U.S affairs bureau.
</P>
<P>
   The United States wants North Korea to halt the development and
export of ballistic missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Pyongyang, however, has said it will not negotiate on its
sovereign right to develop defensive missiles. There are hopes it
may be more flexible on its exports, although they are a vital
source of hard currency for the country.
</P>
<P>
   The latest round of talks in Kuala Lumpur, due to hold a final
session Wednesday, has so far focused on the export issue, Kim
Myong Gil, a member of the North Korean delegation, told reporters
before entering the talks Tuesday. U.S. officials did not speak to
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea has in the past reportedly demanded annual
compensation of $1 billion for three years if it curbs missile
exports.
</P>
<P>
   The United States claims North Korea is the world's top exporter
of missile equipment and technology, with countries such as
Pakistan and Iran as customers.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-1998, Pyongyang rattled Asia by test firing a missile
over Japan into the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the difficulties, Einhorn said Monday that the latest
talks were being held in a positive atmosphere, largely due to a
June summit meeting between North Korean leader Kim Jong Il and
South Korean President Kim Dae-Jung.
</P>
<P>
   The two reached an agreement to reunite some of the many
families that were divided by the 1950-53 Korean War, which ended
without a peace treaty and created the world's most heavily armed
border -- one guarded by thousands of U.S. troops.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea has also recently agreed to a moratorium on tests of
long-range missiles in exchange for an easing of U.S. sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   It has opened official talks with Japan, moved to establish
diplomatic relations with many countries in Asia and Europe, and
joined a security forum of Southeast Asian nations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-11-00 0152 </TRAILER>
