<HEADLINE> Venezuela Editor's Arrest Denounced  </HEADLINE>
By TIMOTHY WARREN
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- A leading Venezuelan press group on
Monday denounced the detention of a newspaper editor charged with
libeling a prominent businessman with ties to President Hugo
Chavez.
</P>
<P>
   Pablo Lopez, editor-in-chief of the Caracas weekly La Razon, was
detained Saturday after skipping repeated court appearances to
answer the charges of libel by the businessman, a top Chavez
campaign contributor.
</P>
<P>
   The Venezuelan Press Association, an organization of newspaper
owners, said Monday that government aggression against the press
was generating a ''perverse motivation, causing state bodies to
support actions contrary to the Constitution and all notions of
human rights.''
</P>
<P>
   In a series of front-page articles last year, La Razon alleged
that an insurance company owned by Tobias Carrero won government
contracts after making hefty contributions to Chavez's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Carrero filed a defamation suit in October.
</P>
<P>
   Judge David Perez ordered Lopez's house arrest when he failed to
show up to a hearing Thursday. But a judicial inspector suspended
Perez on Monday, saying he had acted with ''obvious partiality'' in
the case by not allowing Lopez's lawyers to stage a proper defense.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez has ignored a ruling to stop publishing stories on Carrero
and his company, Multinacional de Seguros. ''We're going to keep on
writing,'' Lopez said.
</P>
<P>
   The president of the legislature, Luis Miquilena, rejected
criticisms of the government's treatment of the press, saying La
Razon writers were ''paid off,'' and that they had criticized
Carrero because ''he didn't buy advertisements.''
</P>
<P>
   Venezuelan press groups say the case is the latest evidence of
increasing tensions between the media and Chavez, first prompted
when the president attacked media owners as ''manipulators'' and
''liars.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Chavez pushed through a new constitution containing
an ambiguous clause requiring news outlets to publish ''truthful''
information. Critics have called it a recipe for censorship, while
supporters have said it deepens freedom of expression for
reporters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
