<HEADLINE> Iranian Leader Visits Germany  </HEADLINE>
By TONY CZUCZKA
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- Iranian President Mohammed Khatami brings his
message of a ''new beginning'' with the West to German business
leaders Tuesday, while exiled opponents of Iran's clerical rulers
promised another day of street protests.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder stressed Germany's interest in
promoting trade in talks Monday. He announced his government would
offer more export credit guarantees for companies trading with Iran
and revive a bilateral panel on economic cooperation dormant since
1991.
</P>
<P>
   Khatami was to meet with Germany's conservative opposition
leader and the mayor of Berlin Tuesday before addressing a group of
German business leaders.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of the security worries accompanying the trip, Khatami
is skipping the traditional walk through Berlin's signature
Brandenburg Gate, where thousands of opponents of Iran's Islamic
rulers protested Monday. More demonstrations were set around the
city for Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder also raised concerns about human rights in Iran during
his meeting with Khatami. German officials said the discussions
included the recent convictions of 10 Iranian Jews as alleged spies
for Israel -- a charge Israel has denied.
</P>
<P>
   German President Johannes Rau met Khatami earlier Monday and
urged Iran to respect minority rights, the president's office said.
</P>
<P>
   Khatami, a moderate cleric, has pursued a course of cautious
liberalization and opening to the West since his 1997 election --
overtures limited to Europe since the United States largely still
shuns Iran. Khatami visited Italy and France last year.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference with Schroeder, Khatami said both sides
should focus on their points of agreement and ''attempt to overcome
the differences in a dialogue. We can also work together well on
economic and political issues.''
</P>
<P>
   German leaders say they wanted to give Khatami support against
powerful Islamic hard-liners who oppose reform. Khatami also is
looking for much-needed investment from Germany, one of his
country's biggest trading partners.
</P>
<P>
   His trip to Germany amid tight security was a sign that both
countries want to look ahead after years of strained or frozen
relations over a German businessman's jailing in Tehran and a
German court ruling that in effect branded Iran a terrorist state.
</P>
<P>
   Khatami was traveling mostly by helicopter, even within Berlin,
and German authorities had stopped an unspecified number of
Iranians at border crossings and airports in recent days after
receiving tips that opposition groups might stage violent
disturbances.
</P>
<P>
   Khatami travels Wednesday to Weimar for events focused on
German-Iranian cultural links before returning to Iran.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-11-00 0211 </TRAILER>
