<HEADLINE> Man gets life in children's murder  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) - A man convicted of the execution-style
murder of two children in their Rochester home was sentenced to
life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Monroe County Court Judge William Bristol listened to convicted
murderer Jose Julian Santiago insist at Monday's sentencing that he
is innocent. Then the judge said: ''You deserve to die in prison,''
the Rochester Democrat and Chronicle reported. ''Have a nice day.''
</P>
<P>
   Santiago, 25, could have been sentenced to death by lethal
injection after a jury found him guilty on June 8 of killing a
14-year-old boy and his 2-year-old nephew during a bungled robbery.
Zyrone Scrivens and his toddler nephew, Drequan, died in their
home.
</P>
<P>
   Santiago was found guilty of first and second-degree murder as
well as attempted first-degree murder for wounding, by shooting and
stabbing, Bernetta ''Goldie'' Wims, 37, and her daughters,
Shuntavia Scrivens, 20, and Chaquita ''Nikki'' Wims, 17.
</P>
<P>
   The women said Santiago, an acquaintance who lived a block away,
talked about being depressed and penniless during a visit to their
home the night of March 1, 1999. They said he then grabbed some
jewelry, demanded cash and turned violent when Wims pleaded she had
none.
</P>
<P>
   Santiago tied them up with telephone cord, blindfolded them and
forced them to lie on a bed, then methodically began shooting and
stabbing each one of them, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Bernetta Wims, whose son and grandson were slain in the attack,
wished Santiago a long life behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   ''I look at it like this: He's going to suffer more,'' she said.
''Now he has to endure and deal with things that we worry about,
like whether someone is coming up behind us to hurt us.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor Richard A. Keenan said Santiago deserves to die
behind bars because he took the lives of two children and gave life
sentences of pain and suffering to their survivors.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no sentence this court can impose that would truly
give back to the victims and this community what was taken,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Santiago - withdrawn and silent through much of the trial -
lashed out as he stood before Bristol and made his first public
comment about his case.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't have a fair trial,'' he said, claiming the jury
lacked evidence to convict him. ''The trial was messed up.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside of the court, Monroe County District Attorney Howard R.
Relin said he was disappointed that Santiago showed no remorse.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've never seen a defendant more despicable, without morals,
without a shred of human decency, than Jose Santiago,'' He said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
