<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 02:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> $100 gun buyback program in Brooklyn  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - Police have launched a gun buyback program in
Brooklyn, aiming to take hundreds of weapons off the streets for
the second straight year.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's program netted 659 weapons in four weeks, police
Commissioner Howard Safir and Brooklyn District Attorney Charles
Hynes said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The new initiative started at the beginning of the month and
will run until August. So far, 10 guns have been turned in.
</P>
<P>
   Under the buyback program, anyone who turns an operable weapon
in at a police station house receives amnesty and a $100 voucher
redeemable at the district attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   The guns will undergo ballistics tests to determine if they've
been used in city crimes, then they will be destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   The program, to be advertised in posters and pamphlets printed
in Chinese, Creole, English, Polish, Spanish and Russian, is funded
by drug forfeiture money. A buyback program begun in 1992 ended in
1995 when the money ran out.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the program say gun owners use the $100 rewards to
purchase newer and more powerful weapons on the black market.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's program was nicknamed ''Turn it in for a Benjamin,''
a reference to Benjamin Franklin, whose face is on the $100 bill.
Police collected an Uzi machine pistol worth $3,000 on the streets,
a three-shot .22-caliber Derringer that could fit in someone's
palm, a 12-gauge shotgun, a sawed-off shotgun and scores of
semiautomatic weapons and revolvers.
</P>
<P>
   There have been 126 homicides in Brooklyn this year, down from
145 during the first half of last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-11-00 0241 </TRAILER>
