<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 02:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fiji Coup Leader May Get Govt. Post  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUVA, Fiji (AP) -- The leader of Fiji's coup, George Speight,
could be offered a Cabinet post when the influential council of
tribal chiefs meets to appoint a new president and government, the
council head said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is a chance,'' Sitiveni Rabuka told the Australian
Broadcasting Corp. ''He's been given so much and I wouldn't be
surprised if they include him on the list.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabuka, who led two coups in 1987 and then ruled as prime
minister for 12 years, is now head of the Great Council of Chiefs,
which has been called upon to put the finishing touches to a
solution to Fiji's 7-week hostage crisis by naming a new president
and government.
</P>
<P>
   Speight has said he will release his 27 hostages and turn in his
rebels' arms as the chiefs meet Thursday. He has said he would not
put his name forward for a Cabinet post, but would accept one if it
were offered by the chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   Speight has been holding the hostages since storming Parliament
on May 19 saying he wanted to protect the interests of indigenous
Fijians and disenfranchise the ethnic Indian minority.
</P>
<P>
   He and the military, which seized control of Fiji 10 days after
Speight's coup, signed an agreement Sunday to end the crisis, which
has paralyzed the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement includes an amnesty for political crimes committed
until Thursday, when military commander Commodore Frank Bainimarama
is to step down as head of state, along with the interim government
he installed a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   It also meets Speight's demands for scrapping Fiji's multiracial
constitution and dumping the democratically elected government of
Mahendra Chaudhry, the country's first ethnic Indian prime
minister. Chaudhry and many of his ministers are Speight's
hostages.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview with a Sydney, Australia, radio
station, Speight denied orchestrating a wave of civil unrest that
has swept over Fiji in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   Speight sympathizers have occupied three police stations, a
military camp, the hydroelectric plant that supplies power to the
main island of Viti Levu, and the tuna plant. They also have
blockaded traffic and shut down a regional airport for two hours.
</P>
<P>
   There were also unconfirmed reports of workers taking over
Telecom Fiji, the state-owned telecommunications company.
</P>
<P>
   ''What must be understood is that Fiji people are acting of
their own accord,'' Speight told 2UE radio.
</P>
</TEXT>
