<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 02:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Big Cat To Cap Inspiring Comeback  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL NEWBERRY
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- A year ago, Andres Galarraga was sitting at home,
watching baseball's All-Star game on TV as chemotherapy drugs
flowed through his body. It could have been one of the lowest
points of his life.
</P>
<P>
   Not for Galarraga. The player nicknamed the Big Cat already
believed he was on his way to a comeback from cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was never negative about it,'' he says. ''As soon as the
doctors told me I would get better and better, I started working
hard to come back.''
</P>
<P>
   One of baseball's most inspiring stories has come full circle,
with the Atlanta Braves' 39-year-old first baseman starting for the
National League in the midsummer classic just 17 months after
doctors discovered a tumor in his lower back.
</P>
<P>
   At least eight players skipped Tuesday night's All-Star game
because of various ailments, and Galarraga's ordeal makes those
guys with broken fingers and sore knees seem rather wimpy.
Pittsburgh's Jason Kendall, who suffered a grotesque ankle injury
last season, knows his own comeback was overshadowed by
Galarraga's.
</P>
<P>
   ''It should be,'' says Kendall, the National League's starting
catcher. ''I dislocated my ankle. He was dealing with his life.
There's no comparison.''
</P>
<P>
   Major leaguers Eric Davis, Darryl Strawberry and Mike Lowell
have all beaten cancer in recent years. But Galarraga missed an
entire season at an age when most players contemplate retirement
and the disease attacked a part of the body that is critical to
swinging a bat.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves weren't exactly confident he would recapture his
swing. They insisted that Wally Joyner be included in a trade with
San Diego, providing insurance at first base. They told Galarraga
to go easy at spring training, figuring he would need a month or
two to build up the strength in his back and regain his timing.
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga wouldn't hear of it. By opening day, he looked like
the same hitter who averaged 44 home runs and 137 runs batted in
during the three seasons before cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ''I knew he would still be strong,'' says Braves outfielder
Andruw Jones, a fellow All-Star. ''But to see him come in and swing
the bat like he was swinging right away, that was crazy. I was
getting chills.''
</P>
<P>
   He reached the All-Star break hitting .294 with 20 homers and 62
RBIs for the first-place Braves. Galarraga was named to the
starting lineup when Mark McGwire backed out because of an injured
knee.
</P>
<P>
   New York Yankees manager Joe Torre, who recovered from a bout
with prostate cancer last season, says Galarraga's comeback is one
of the most inspiring stories in sports, matched only by cyclist
Lance Armstrong's recovery from the disease to win the Tour de
France.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no question when you hear that 'C' word, the only
thing you associate with it is death,'' Torre says. ''It's not
really that dark hole you initially think. But to have Andres come
back. I mean, I come back and sit on my rear end.''
</P>
<P>
   There were grim moments for Galarraga during his treatment. The
chemo caused nausea and a weight gain of some 40 pounds, making it
difficult for him to even to look at his once-sculpted body in the
mirror.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, though, Galarraga never lost faith. By the
time of last year's All-Star game, the chemo had destroyed 75
percent of the tumor, convincing him that he would beat the
disease.
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga considers himself an inspiration to others dealing
with cancer. As an All-Star before his hometown fans, he didn't
rule out a few tears flowing down his cheeks.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no words to explain,'' Galarraga says, ''how good I
feel.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-11-00 0252 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
