<HEADLINE> Dow Jumps 126; Nasdaq Climbs 29  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks moved higher Tuesday as high-tech shares
recovered from a bout of profit-taking in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
   The market also got a boost from an upbeat speech on
productivity and the New Economy from Federal Reserve Chairman Alan
Greenspan.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average was up 126.22 to 10,772.80 in
midday trading, while the Nasdaq composite index rose 29.39 to
4,009.68, coming back from a slight decline at the open of trading.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 9.22 at 1,484.84.
</P>
<P>
   Intel was among the blue-chip tech shares enjoying a rebound
Tuesday morning after a dropoff the previous day. The chip maker's
shares were up $3.19 at $141; Applied Materials was up $2.18 at
$90.81; and Analog Devices rose $3.25 to $78.63.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech to the National Governors' Association, Greenspan
repeated his views that the explosion in use of the computer and
other high-tech devices has boosted America's productivity growth,
the amount of output for each hour of work. Increased productivity
has been a primary contributor to the nation's long economic
expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan didn't give any indication about whether the Fed would
raise interest rates at its August meeting. Investors have been
hoping the the Fed may be finished raising rates for now following
its six increases over the past year.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, trading was quiet as the corporate earnings season got
under way, but so far the announcements have been encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   Aluminum maker Alcoa reported stronger-than-expected earnings
Monday, and International Paper followed suit with its own strong
earnings report Tuesday. Shares of Alcoa were up $1.813 at $31.813,
and IP shares were up $1.625 at $33.875.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo's shares were off $8.44 $101.56 ahead of the company's
earnings announcement later in the day. Motorcycle maker
Harley-Davidson also reports its second-quarter earnings Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered declining issues by a margin of 11
to 9 on the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 441.21
million shares.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index rose 1.78 to 532.61.
</P>
