<HEADLINE> Daley Bids Farewell to Commerce  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- ''Flowery farewells are not my style,''
Commerce Secretary Bill Daley said Tuesday, taking a break from the
Gore campaign to say goodbye to thousands of department employees.
</P>
<P>
   ''I did want to get together -- not to say goodbye -- but to say
thank you,'' said Daley, whose last day as the department's chief
is Friday. ''Thanks for all of the help you have given me these
last 3&AMP;frac12; years.''
</P>
<P>
   Daley took over last month as chairman of Vice President Al
Gore's presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have loved every minute of this job. I will miss all of
you,'' an emotional Daley told Commerce employees packed into the
department's cavernous lobby. He assumed the helm in January 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Daley recalled his introduction to department employees as
President Clinton's nominee in December 1996. He hadn't taken time
to eat that day and fainted on the stage as Clinton was speaking.
''People in the front row may want to back up,'' Daley joked.
</P>
<P>
   Former Rep. Norman Mineta, D-Calif., an executive with Lockheed
Martin Corp., has been tapped by Clinton to lead the Commerce
Department and become the first Asian-American Cabinet secretary.
</P>
</TEXT>
