<HEADLINE> Greenspan Upbeat; Stocks Move Higher  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue chip stocks moved higher Tuesday following
an upbeat speech on productivity and the New Economy from Federal
Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average was up 79.55 to 10,726.13 in
early afternoon trading. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index also rose,
gaining 1.65 to 1,477.27.
</P>
<P>
   Tech stocks pulled back from a rally earlier in the day, sending
the Nasdaq composite index down 22.16 to 3,958.13.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech to the National Governors' Association, Greenspan
repeated his views that the explosion in use of the computer and
other high-tech devices has boosted America's productivity growth,
the amount of output for each hour of work. Increased productivity
has been a primary contributor to the nation's long economic
expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan didn't give any indication about whether the Fed would
raise interest rates at its August meeting. Investors have been
hoping the the Fed may be finished raising rates for now following
its six increases over the past year.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo shares slumped, losing $9.25 to $100.75, although the
Internet bellwether was expected to announce strong earnings later
in the day. Other Internet companies followed Yahoo lower,
including America Online, down $2 at $53.75; and Amazon, down
$2.375 at $32.688.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, trading was quiet as the corporate earnings season got
under way, but so far the announcements have been encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   Aluminum maker Alcoa reported stronger-than-expected earnings
Monday, and International Paper followed suit with its own strong
earnings report Tuesday. Shares of Alcoa were up $2.313 at $32.313,
and IP shares were up $1.944 at $34.188.
</P>
<P>
   Motorcycle maker Harley-Davidson also reports its second-quarter
earnings Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered declining issues by a margin of 11
to 9 on the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 663.19
million shares.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index fell 1.00 to 529.83.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
