<HEADLINE> French Journalists Held Hostage  </HEADLINE>
By AARON FAVILA
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOLO, Philippines (AP) -- A French journalist missing in a remote
jungle used a satellite telephone Tuesday to tell Philippine
officials that she and two colleagues have been taken hostage by
Muslim rebels already holding at least 33 other captives, many of
them foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   The journalists from the French TV2 agency failed to return
Sunday after traveling to a camp held by the Abu Sayyaf rebels to
interview the hostages, who include 20 tourists snatched from a
nearby Malaysian diving resort on April 23.
</P>
<P>
   Chief government negotiator Robert Aventajado said Maryse Burgot
called his aide and said they were being held by the Abu Sayyaf,
but the journalist did not disclose other details.
</P>
<P>
   The aide said Burgot pleaded in a shaking voice to talk with
Philippine President Joseph Estrada. Burgot did not say if the
rebels were demanding a ransom for their release.
</P>
<P>
   The French journalists -- Burgot, Jean-Jacques Legarrec and
Roland Madura -- were among the few foreign reporters still covering
the hostage crisis on southern Jolo island. Most others left after
a German reporter for Der Speigel magazine, Andreas Lorenz, was
abducted by armed men on July 2. He is also believed to held at an
Abu Sayyaf camp.
</P>
<P>
   Aventajado said he also was able to talk with an Abu Sayyaf
commander, Ghalib Andang, using the French journalists' satellite
phone.
</P>
<P>
   Andang, who also uses the name Commander Robot, offered to
release the hostages in exchange for a ransom of about $1 million
each, Aventajado's aide said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Let's talk. We have already 36 hostages, there are too many
hostages here already,'' Andang said, according to Aventajado.
Andang apparently did not include Lorenz in his count. His group is
also believed to be holding three Filipinos kidnapped recently on
nearby Basilan island.
</P>
<P>
   Andang did confirm that the rebels are also holding 13 Christian
evangelists who traveled to the Abu Sayyaf camp on July 1 to pray
for the 20 original captives, Aventajado said.
</P>
<P>
   The Muslim rebels have accused the Christians, who belong to a
group called the Jesus Miracle Crusade, of bringing along police
spies disguised as evangelists and of showing disrespect to Islam.
</P>
<P>
   For the preachers' freedom, the guerrillas are demanding that
government troops abandon camps they have seized from the Moro
Islamic Liberation Front, a separate group of Muslim rebels who are
also fighting for a separate Islamic state in the southern
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   The capture of the evangelists further complicates government
efforts to free the original 20 hostages, some of whom have become
ill from their long jungle captivity. A 21st hostage, a Malaysian
kidnapped with them, was freed last month.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, German hostage Werner Wallert wrote to Estrada,
asking him to allow the payment of about $1 million in ransom for
the release of his wife, Renate, the most ill of the captives.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said they would abide by the government's no-ransom
policy.
</P>
<P>
   Estrada called the Abu Sayyaf guerrillas ''crazy and very
callous'' but said his administration's primary concern remains
''the safety of the hostages,'' suggesting he was not entertaining
a military solution.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
