<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arabs Watching Camp David Closely  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA BRYSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- As if the hopes of the Palestinians were not
pressure enough, Yasser Arafat also carried with him to Camp David
on Tuesday the hopes of Arabs from across the region.
</P>
<P>
   They want him to return with at least part of Jerusalem in Arab
hands, and with a solution for the refugees crowded into camps in
Jordan, Lebanon and Syria -- touching on two of the most difficult
issues before Palestinian and Israeli negotiators at the summit
President Clinton opened Tuesday at Camp David, Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   In Egypt on the eve of the summit, President Hosni Mubarak's
chief political aide, Osama el-Baz, told reporters that Arabs
throughout the region, Muslim and Christian, had a stake in
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   ''President Arafat is not free in dealing with the Jerusalem
issue fully as long as there are other dimensions apart from the
Palestinian dimension,'' el-Baz said, noting there were also
''Jewish rights and dimensions.''
</P>
<P>
   Israel insists that the city so holy to Muslims, Jews and
Christians will remain united under its sovereignty. The
Palestinians want east Jerusalem as their future capital.
</P>
<P>
   Camp David is known as the place where treaties are forged. The
mountain retreat is where then-President Jimmy Carter brought the
Israelis and the Egyptians close to their 1979 peace, the first in
the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   But Michel Edde, a former Lebanese Cabinet minister who closely
follows Israeli-Lebanese affairs, expected no Camp David
breakthroughs this time.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat, he said, is under great pressure not to compromise, both
from Palestinians and other Arabs. Meanwhile, Barak is weakened by
the collapse of his governing coalition.
</P>
<P>
   ''There can be no settlement without east Jerusalem coming into
Arab hands. Not only in Palestine, but in Egypt, in all Arab
countries, in all Islamic countries, it is an absolute
requirement,'' Edde said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, his country is the uneasy host of some 350,000
Palestinian refugees, scattered across 13 squalid camps. Lebanon
denies them citizenship rights. Edde said Lebanon, riven by
unemployment and Muslim-Christian tensions, cannot afford to give
them a permanent home should Israeli and Palestinian negotiators
fail to agree that they can return to the homes they lost in the
wars and unrest that followed Israel's founding in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   ''We cannot give Palestinians jobs here when our children do not
have jobs,'' he said. ''It is not a solution.''
</P>
<P>
   The sentiment is similar in Jordan, where an estimated 1.5
million Palestinian refugees form the bulk of the population.
</P>
<P>
   ''Jordan takes a firm stand in refusing to accept a new influx
or to absorb any refugee -- whoever he may be and under any
pretext,'' Jordanian Prime Minister Ali Abu-Ragheb told his
parliament Sunday. His declaration followed unsubstantiated
newspaper reports of a hidden U.S.-Israeli plan to resettle in
Jordan an estimated 750,000 Palestinian refugees now in Lebanon and
Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has said there will be no blanket ''right of return'' for
Palestinians displaced in 1948 and 1967 wars.
</P>
<P>
   In Syria, where an estimated 350,000 Palestinians have found
refuge, a militant Palestinian leader feared Arafat would not be
able to stand up to pressure applied by Barak and Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ''Regretfully, what is happening is very painful and the
Palestinian people and the Arab nation will be the only ones to pay
the price,'' Ahmed Jibril, leader of the Damascus-based Popular
Front for the Liberation of Palestine-General Command, said in a
statement Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Khaldoun Abu Ruman, a 77-year-old Palestinian living in Amman,
Jordan's Wehdat Camp, was equally pessimistic.
</P>
<P>
   Israelis ''are strong and we are weak. Why should a man leave
your house while he is standing there, pointing a gun at you?
Because you ask him gently? No. That will not happen,'' he said
Tuesday. ''I wish to die in my homeland. I wish to see it again, at
least once before I die.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
