<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Ponders Effective Speech  </HEADLINE>
By CLAUDE R. MARX
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A reflective President Clinton says that even
after a lifetime in politics he still cannot predict what things he
says in a speech will have the most impact.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have no formula, a lot of it is just instinct,'' he told
reporters Monday on Air Force One during a flight from State
College, Pa. to Philadelphia. ''You just never know what people
hear.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had addressed the National Governors Association summer
meeting at the university town and stopped en route to his plane to
get a cone of ''Peachy Paterno'' ice cream -- named after Penn State
football coach Joe Paterno -- at the creamery on the campus.
</P>
<P>
   He said figuring out how to communicate ideas effectively is ''a
continuing challenge, almost a riddle.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton added that because attention spans vary it is difficult
to gauge how best to persuade people to agree with his policies.
</P>
<P>
   ''Most people are more like flowers in the morning. They open up
for a while and they close down for a while because they've got
other things to deal with in their lives and they can't take all
that incoming information,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Two former speechwriters for presidents of different parties had
a different view. They said they often could guess what resonates
with the public.
</P>
<P>
   ''You usually do know what will hit,'' said Clark Judge who
wrote for President Reagan during both of his terms. ''One of the
differences is that he (Reagan) had a more focused message that we
were driving. You have to have something to say and people have to
take you seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Theodore Sorensen, who wrote for President Kennedy, said they
were able to predict what language would have the desired effect on
the audience.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think that President Kennedy and I had some sense of the
lines that would inform, as distinct from those that stirred
people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sorensen said Clinton is being ''unduly modest'' because the
president is one of the most effective modern political speakers,
especially in small settings.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he read several books on personal communications
but they have not given him any great revelations about how to
better hone his rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   He added that Vice President Al Gore's address to next month's
Democratic Convention would require different skills than a regular
speech and must target three audiences: the crowd in the hall,
television viewers and those who read newspaper accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was defensive about his nominating speech at the 1988
Democratic National Convention, often criticized for being too
long. He said he sent three versions of the speech to the campaign
of Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis and they chose the longest
one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-11-00 1549 </TRAILER>
