<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NTSB Warns Cruise Lines About Fires  </HEADLINE>
By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Cruise ship companies should drop their
opposition to installing individual smoke detectors in crew and
passenger quarters, federal safety investigators said Tuesday,
warning that smoke from fires onboard endangers thousands of lives.
</P>
<P>
   The National Transportation Safety Board, reporting on its
investigation of fires aboard five cruise ships over the past four
years, said it could not accept the cruise industry's objections to
the safety devices. The board first urged the installation of local
smoke detectors on cruise ships in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ''The No. 1 concern that the safety board has with regard to
cruise ship safety is fire,'' said board chairman Jim Hall. ''They
(cruise ship companies) really have failed to deal in good faith
with the American people on this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the International Council of Cruise Lines said
the organization expected to respond quickly to the request.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, the safety board noted that 6 million passengers
boarded cruise ships in American ports last year alone.
</P>
<P>
   ''These passengers are every day placed in danger because the
ships lack an important safety item, a local sounding alarm,'' the
board said.
</P>
<P>
   The safety board said that the cruise line industry opposed
recommendations first made by the board in 1997 after its
investigations of fires aboard the Universe Explorer off Alaska and
the Bahamian passenger ship Vista Fjord en route to the Azores.
Five crewmen died of smoke inhalation aboard the Universe Explorer
and 67 crew members and two passengers were injured.
</P>
<P>
   The ICCL, the voice of the industry, opposed the proposals
before the International Maritime Organization on grounds that
individual smoke detectors produce numerous false alarms which
could result in mass panic aboard ship
</P>
<P>
   The safety board rejected these arguments and called on the
cruise industry to withdraw its opposition and support a full
discussion on the issues.
</P>
<P>
   It said its original 1997 proposal did not envision the
automatic triggering of a ship-wide automatic alarm based on the
activation of a single local or cabin smoke alarm.
</P>
<P>
   ''Therefore the local alarm could not be expected to result in a
mass panic situation,'' the board said.
</P>
<P>
   But it said that since a smoke alarm would result in alerting
the ship's central fire control station, ''the crew could be
immediately informed of the activated alarm and would be able to
launch an appropriate response without delay.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the fires aboard the Universe Explorer and the Vista
Fjord, the safety board has investigated three other cruise ship
fires. These nonfatal fires occurred aboard the Ecstasy in 1998,
the Tropicale in 1999 and the Nieuw Amsterdam this year. The safety
board said there were nearly 9,000 people aboard the five ships
when the fires occurred.
</P>
<P>
   The safety board said the additional ship fires underscore the
need for automatic smoke-detector alarms in crew and passenger
spaces.
</P>
<P>
   ''Had these ships been equipped with automatic local-sounding
smoke alarms, the injured individuals would have had earlier
warning of smoke, would then have had more time in which to escape,
and probably would not have been trapped or injured,'' the safety
board said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   International Council of Cruise Lines: http://www.iccl.org
</P>
<P>
   National Transportation Safety Board: http://www.ntsb.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
