<HEADLINE> Russia Braces for Chechen Attacks  </HEADLINE>
By LYOMA TURPALOV
<TEXT>
<P>
   GUDERMES, Russia (AP) -- Bracing for renewed attacks by Chechen
militants, Russian authorities tightened security Tuesday in Moscow
and elsewhere across Russia, and fearful civilians fled large
Chechen cities in anticipation of new fighting.
</P>
<P>
   The military has been warning that the rebels were planning
terrorist attacks, and amplified the alarm after a series of
bombings last week that killed at least 33 troops and wounded
scores more. Eleven civilians perished in the blasts in four towns,
Russian officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Chechen civilians received rebel warnings to leave the breakaway
region's largest cities including the capital Grozny, the northern
town of Gudermes -- where the pro-Moscow Chechen government has its
headquarters -- and Urus-Martan in the southwest, the independent
NTV television reported.
</P>
<P>
   They were leaving these towns in buses, Russian media said.
Meanwhile, a woman was injured in Grozny on Tuesday by a
remote-controlled bomb.
</P>
<P>
   Col. Gennady Alyokhin, a military spokesman, confirmed that
Russian forces were bracing for rebel attacks, with Grozny,
Gudermes and Urus-Martan as the ''most likely sites.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Alyokhin and the Kremlin-installed leader of Chechnya,
Akhmad Kadyrov, however, said the militants were unable to stage
large-scale attacks and were mainly trying to whip up tension.
</P>
<P>
   ''Terrorist acts are possible, but no state can be insured
against them,'' said Kadyrov.
</P>
<P>
   In Moscow, police and security agents were checking suspicious
trucks and abandoned vehicles, fearing car bombs, according to
spokesmen for city police and the FSB domestic security agency.
Other measures in Moscow and elsewhere included roadblocks and
searches of apartment houses' attics and cellars.
</P>
<P>
   Police in Moscow said they were checking every bomb rumor and
evacuating residents if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   The current war in Chechnya began after a series of bloody
apartment house bombings in Moscow and other Russian towns last
year, which the Kremlin blamed on Chechen militants. Moscow Mayor
Yuri Luzhkov warned Tuesday the attacks could be repeated.
</P>
<P>
   ''I do not want to spread any panic or hysteria, I just ask
everyone to be attentive and cautious, since the situation in the
Caucasus makes this necessary,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, Russian forces tightened security on the border
between rebel Chechnya and neighboring region of Ingushetia, which
included more searches and dogs sniffing vehicles for explosives.
</P>
<P>
   Border checkpoints also closed earlier than usual despite a
growing number of refugees trying to cross into Ingushetia, the
ITAR-Tass news agency said. Some 450 people entered Chechnya from
Ingushetia over the past 24 hours, it said.
</P>
<P>
   A Russian policeman was wounded Monday evening when the driver
of a car he was trying to search opened fire with a pistol. The
driver was killed but a passenger in the car escaped, Russian
reports said.
</P>
<P>
   Russian aircraft flew about 90 combat missions over the past 24
hours, the military said Tuesday. They concentrated their fire on
the southern Vedeno and Argun Gorges, where rebels have taken
refuge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
