<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kidnapping suspect dies in police custody  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   RIDGEFIELD, N.J. (AP) - A man who police say tried
unsuccessfully to kidnap a woman over an unpaid business debt died
of a heart attack while in police custody, authorities said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Bergen County Prosecutor William H. Schmidt said Chong Dae Kim,
45, of Palisades Park died Monday at Holy Name Hospital, where he
was taken after complaining of chest pains at police headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   He was arrested earlier in the day along with two other suspects
in connection with the attempted abduction of a woman as she got
into her car at 1:47 p.m. Police said Kim grabbed the woman and
tried to shove her into his vehicle, but she fought off her
attackers.
</P>
<P>
   The suspects then fled but were nabbed by police a few minutes
later.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt said all three suspects were arrested and taken to
police headquarters without incident.
</P>
<P>
   At 2:32 p.m., while at police headquarters, Kim complained of
chest pains, and an ambulance was called. He was taken to the
hospital at 3:08 p.m, where he was pronounced dead at 6:13 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   An autopsy performed Tuesday by the Bergen County Medical
Examiner's Office determined the cause of death to be a heart
attack from natural causes. Schmidt said Kim had a history of
hypertension and an enlarged heart.
</P>
<P>
   The other suspects were identified as Jong Sung Kim, 40, of
Elmhurst, N.Y., the brother of the dead man, and Chong S. Shin, 25,
of Palisades Park. They are charged with attempted kidnapping,
aggravated assault and criminal restraint.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt said the victim had borrowed $8,000 from John Sung Kim
in June and was required to pay 10 percent weekly interest, Last
week, the woman was only able to pay back $500 instead of $800. The
prosecutor said the attempted abduction appears to be in
retaliation for the shortfall.
</P>
</TEXT>
