<HEADLINE> Residents, Pinelands Commission at odds over sewer link  </HEADLINE>
By BRENDAN SCHURR
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEMBERTON TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) - Fe Wise loves to eat dinner
outside on her deck in the summer. There's just one problem: She
often has to endure the odor of overflowing septic tanks.
</P>
<P>
   Wise and many of her neighbors in the 880-house Presidential
Lakes development have tolerated the sludge and the smell for
years. They are anxious for the township to link them to a public
sewer system, but doing so would conflict with the growth
management plan of the Pinelands Commission, which oversees the
1.1-million acre, environmentally sensitive Pine Barrens.
</P>
<P>
   The commission says a public health hazard must be proved before
a sewer link can be built.
</P>
<P>
   In the 21 years that Wise and her family have lived in their
house, the septic tank has overflowed too many times to count, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's terrible. We can't stand it. It's in your yard, and it
smells,'' she said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Wise lives in a cluster of homes that have been particularly
hard hit. Her next-door neighbor, Donna Kitson, has had her septic
system back up into her house several times.
</P>
<P>
   ''One time it was above my ankles,'' she said. ''We were redoing
two rooms. We had just put new carpet in and were working on the
walls and woodwork. It was all ruined. We never redid the rooms.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pine Barrens encompass about 22 percent of New Jersey. The
Pinelands Commission has designated some sections as growth areas,
but is charged with limiting development in other regions, like the
forest area that includes Presidential Lakes.
</P>
<P>
   The commission instituted its Comprehensive Management Plan in
1981, about 11 years after Presidential Lakes was built.
</P>
<P>
   ''The division itself, for sure, would not have been approved
now,'' Michael Broek, spokesman for the Pinelands Commission, said
Tuesday. ''You can't cram all these things into a forest area.''
</P>
<P>
   The lots in Presidential Lakes are about 10,000 square feet
each. Under the Pinelands Commission's regulations, houses in
forest areas would need a minimum of 3.5 acres each today, Broek
said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the main reasons for this is to limit the amount of
nitrogen that is released into the ground. Most of what is
discharged from a septic system is nitrogen. The typical Pinelands
environment is ''nitrogen-poor,'' Broek said.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's great for the Pinelands flora and fauna. If you start
to raise the nitrogen levels in the ground water, you start to push
out native species and bring in invasive species,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If it were determined that a public health threat exists, sewer
extensions could be put into the affected homes only, Broek said.
</P>
<P>
   The township is sampling wells in the development to gauge
whether nitrates discharged by septic systems have contaminated the
well water.
</P>
<P>
   Nitrates are a byproduct of human waste and of some fertilizers.
When ingested by humans or animals, they are converted into
nitrites and can rob the blood of oxygen.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-one percent of 385 respondents to a Burlington County
survey said their septic system was malfunctioning. The expected
rate of failure is 5 percent, according to the county.
</P>
<P>
   County health workers also have been visually inspecting
randomly selected septic systems and have found that 5 percent
appear to be malfunctioning.
</P>
<P>
   The Pinelands Commission will determine whether there is a
health hazard based on water tests being conducted by the township
and the county. The commission has not received the county's report
on its resident survey, Broek said.
</P>
<P>
   Township and Burlington County officials did not return several
messages Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Broek said rather than linking the homes to a public sewer
system, it would be less expensive and less intrusive on the
environment to put in public water.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the problem is contaminated ground water, it would be much
cheaper - and is within the Comprehensive Management Plan - to
bring in a public water line,'' he said. ''A public sewer line
would be extremely expensive, and they have the problem, where are
they going to take it? It would have to be taken to a treatment
plant and would have to go through miles of virgin forest.''
</P>
<P>
   A public water line also would solve the problem, long
complained about by residents, of brown water high in iron.
Residents say the water smells like rotten eggs, damages their
teeth and stains their clothes.
</P>
<P>
   ''Those problems would be solved by public water,'' Broek said.
''That's why the provision is in the plan. If people are stuck and
their water is getting fouled, then we do want to do something
about it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
