<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 17:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pataki: Balkans 'fascinating,' but trip was no vacation  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Gov. George Pataki's trip to the Balkans and
Germany entailed everything from meetings with opponents of
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to a chance encounter with
former Russian leader Mikhail Gorbachev.
</P>
<P>
   ''I enjoyed it very much on an intellectual level,'' Pataki told
reporters Tuesday. ''It wasn't a particularly relaxing and
enjoyable journey.''
</P>
<P>
   But Pataki said he was delighted to find during a stop in Berlin
on the way home that former Russian President Gorbachev was staying
in the next room at his hotel. Gorbachev invited Pataki, state
Economic Development chief Charles Gargano and Pataki adviser Zenia
Mucha into his room for a late-night discussion.
</P>
<P>
   ''We spent over an hour talking about politics, history, the
future, his view of the Balkans, his view of America, his view of
Russia,'' Pataki said. ''It was absolutely fascinating to have that
chance to talk to one of the figures who, when the 20th century is
looked back on with some distance, will really have played a
historic role.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki said the discussion with Gorbachev, who presided over the
breakup of the former Soviet Union, was especially meaningful
coming in a city once split by that symbol of communist repression,
the Berlin Wall.
</P>
<P>
   Language was only a slight barrier. Mucha, a Polish immigrant,
translated Pataki's comments into Ukrainian for Gorbachev.
Gorbachev spoke Russian, which his German translator converted into
English, Mucha said.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki was among about 20 North American and European scholars,
politicians and diplomats who spent four days starting June 25 in
the Balkans on a fact-finding trip arranged by the American
Enterprise Institute's New Atlantic Initiative. It is a group
designed to foster better American-European relations.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki said the three primary stops of the delegation - Kosovo,
Bosnia and Montenegro - were all troubling in their own way.
</P>
<P>
   He said the depth of ethnic hatred in Kosovo between Serbs and
Kosovars was of a ''magnitude that I've never seen before.'' Troops
must be kept in place to simply prevent one faction from killing
the other, Pataki said.
</P>
<P>
   Bosnia remains under the thumb of Milosevic while Montenegro is
''one of the most beautiful places I've ever seen,'' but is
regarded as too dangerous to attract tourists, Pataki said.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the group talked to opposition leaders as well as
ruling government officials in each country, Pataki said.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights activist Bianca Jagger, ex-wife of Rolling Stone
singer Mick Jagger, was among those on the trip.
</P>
<P>
   ''She was very serious and she was very hardworking and very
well-prepared,'' Pataki said. ''It was clear that she was serious
about her human rights activities. This isn't just something to
keep one's name in the press.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki said he gave Texas Gov. George W. Bush some of his
impressions of the trip and expected to provide more details to the
Republican presidential candidate's policy team.
</P>
<P>
   In Berlin, Pataki said he talked up New York business
opportunities before the German Chamber of Commerce. Discussions
are underway to try to lure one German company interested in
opening a North American headquarters to New York, according to the
governor.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki refused to identify the company, lest it sour on New York
or the state tip its hand to competitors in other states.
</P>
<P>
   ''I certainly don't want New Jersey or Pennsylvania to know what
companies are looking to establishing a North American
headquarters,'' Pataki said. ''Let them go to Berlin and find
out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
