<HEADLINE> Group protests Wal-Mart decision not to sell Preven  </HEADLINE>
AP Photo
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMHERST, N.Y. (AP) - About a dozen people gathered outside a
Wal-Mart store Tuesday to protest the retailer's decision not to
sell the morning-after pill at its pharmacy counters nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters from Zero Population Growth and Planned
Parenthood accused Wal-Mart of succumbing to pressure by abortion
foes opposed to the drug which can be used after unprotected sex to
stop a pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   The Buffalo-area protest was the eighth in a series of
demonstrations Zero Population Growth has been staging around the
country. Another protest was planned for Wednesday in Rochester.
</P>
<P>
   ''We think they've made a political decision,'' said ZPG
president Peter Kostmayer said.
</P>
<P>
   A Wal-Mart spokeswoman said the decision ''has absolutely
nothing to do with morals.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It was based on several business factors,'' Jessica Moser said
from the company's Bentonville, Ark., headquarters, ''one being
customer demand for the product.
</P>
<P>
   ''We already carry a broad assortment of birth control products
and as in any category of products we carry we want to have the
products on the shelf that we're seeing customer demand for,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters carried a sign with the message ''Wal-Mart is rolling
back Buffalo women's rights.''
</P>
