<HEADLINE> 31 horses dead in barn fire  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NORTH SALEM, N.Y. (AP) - Fire raced through a barn at a horse
farm in northern Westchester, killing 31 horses, many of them
mounts for children learning to ride.
</P>
<P>
   The blaze at Breakaway Farms on Route 121 in North Salem broke
out at about 5:15 a.m. Monday, and the wooden structure was
engulfed by the time firefighters arrived, said Chief Neil Caputo
of the Croton Falls Fire Department, which serves North Salem.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a horrible thing to see,'' he said Tuesday. ''There was
no way to get the horses out when we got here.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators from Westchester County's Fire Control department
had not settled on what caused the fire, but a report was expected
within a couple of days, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen of the horses belonged to Sonia Toker and Martha
Gilchrist, who leased the barn from Oak Brook Farm to run a riding,
boarding and training concern. Fifteen were privately owned and
boarded at Breakaway, many by children learning to ride.
</P>
<P>
   The barn was reduced to an ashen outline and a few blackened
posts. The dead horses were quickly buried by barn workers and
firefighters using the heavy equipment that had been brought in to
extinguish any hot spots.
</P>
<P>
   Kristine Ward, co-owner of Oak Brook, said she was asleep just
25 yards from the barn, unaware of the fire until her dogs started
barking at arriving fire trucks.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is just an incredible tragedy,'' she said. ''There's no
way to make it better.''
</P>
<P>
   Ward is the ex-wife of Barney Ward, a horse trainer who was
sentenced to prison in 1996 after admitting he arranged the deaths
of horses in Illinois for insurance money.
</P>
<P>
   A neighbor, Laura Schwartz, said she saw ''a wall of flame''
shooting up from the barn when she awoke.
</P>
<P>
   Katherine Grayson, whose daughter had a horse at the barn, said
of the animal, ''He was her life.''
</P>
<P>
   ''For her, it's like losing a child,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Another neighbor, Debbie Kilcullen, said Breakaway Farms was
''kid-oriented,'' with horse shows and a summer camp.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a fire at a Brooklyn stable killed 21 horses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
