<HEADLINE> Pataki on VP: I love my job, but ...  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Pressed on what he would tell George W. Bush
if asked to become his vice presidential running mate, New York
Gov. George Pataki continued to duck the question on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I love my job, I really do, and there are a lot of good people
out there, a lot of names Governor Bush is looking at who would be
just terrific,'' Pataki said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if that meant he would decline such an offer from the
Texas governor and presumptive Republican presidential nominee,
Pataki wouldn't say.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not going to say what I may or may not talk to Governor
Bush about, if I may or may not have discussions with Governor
Bush,'' the New York governor said.
</P>
<P>
   Pressed about whether he would accept a cabinet post in a Bush
administration, Pataki repeated his earlier comment. ''I love my
job. I love being governor of New York. It's a great job,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   A source familiar with the governor's thinking, who spoke only
on condition of anonymity, said later Tuesday that Pataki was not
taking himself out of the running for vice president.
</P>
<P>
   The two-term governor of New York, who was a year ahead of Bush
at Yale University in their undergraduate years, has been careful
not to reveal anything about his possible discussions with the Bush
camp over the vice presidency. Pataki has refused to even confirm
that he filled out a vice presidential questionnaire sent out by
Bush's search team.
</P>
<P>
   But Republican officials say Pataki, along with fellow GOP
governors Tom Ridge of Pennsylvania and Frank Keating of Oklahoma,
are among those under serious consideration by Bush as possible
running mates.
</P>
<P>
   In Bush's deliberations, Keating has the advantage of being
anti-abortion and would thus not rile religious right voters as
Pataki and Ridge, both abortion rights supporters, might.
</P>
<P>
   But Pataki and Ridge both come from large electoral vote states,
an attraction for any presidential candidate. Ridge is a decorated
Vietnam War veteran and is considered more likely than Pataki to
deliver his state to Bush in November. Pataki has a record as the
nation's top tax-cutting governor, is well-liked by
environmentalists and drove liberal icon Mario Cuomo from the New
York governorship in 1994.
</P>
</TEXT>
