<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EPA Regulations on Mercury Backed  </HEADLINE>
By H. JOSEF HEBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A panel of the National Academy of Sciences on
Tuesday endorsed a decision by the Environmental Protection Agency
to adopt more stringent levels of protection from mercury, saying
the agency had used ''scientifically justifiable'' studies in its
action.
</P>
<P>
   The academy study claims that while most people are not at high
risk of health problems from low-dose mercury exposure, children of
women who consume large amounts of fish and seafood during their
pregnancy may be ''at special risks'' of having neurological
problems, including learning disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   The findings were expected to ease the way for the EPA to
develop new regulations requiring a reduction of mercury emissions
from coal-burning power plants, which spew 40 tons of mercury into
the air annually, much of which ends up in the food chain.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA's proposed mercury rule has been held up for nearly two
years because Congress barred the agency from proceeding until the
Academy's study was completed.
</P>
<P>
   The 10-member panel in its report concludes that methyl-mercury
''is widespread and persistent in the environment'' and that the
guidelines used by the EPA to establish maximum exposure levels are
''scientifically justifiable ... for the protection of public
health.''
</P>
<P>
   The EPA has asked the utility industry to provide more
information about mercury releases out of power plant smokestacks
and is considering regulations that would require the industry to
curtail such emissions.
</P>
<P>
   The Academy's findings are ''very, very helpful'' in
establishing that the agency's mercury decisions are based on sound
science, said EPA spokesman David Cohen. He said the agency is
required under the Clean Air Act to determine whether new emissions
controls are needed to deal with mercury contamination.
</P>
<P>
   While much remains to be learned about low-dose mercury
contamination and human health, the study says there is strong
evidence to link mercury to neurological, immune system and heart
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ''More must be done to gain a better understanding of various
risk factors for the U.S. population'' from mercury exposure, said
Robert A. Goyer, chairman of the 10-member review panel. He said
while the EPA guidelines are ''adequate,'' more needs to be learned
about regional differences, and effects on population groups whose
diets are high in fish and seafood.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need to better understand how this chemical affects brain
development in fetuses and children,'' Goyer said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   EPA: http://www.epa.gov
</P>
<P>
   National Academy of Sciences: http://ww.nas.edu
</P>
</TEXT>
