<HEADLINE> House OKs Farm Spending Bill  </HEADLINE>
By PHILIP BRASHER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House approved a $75.3 billion spending
bill for farm programs and food regulation after farm-state
lawmakers defeated attempts Tuesday to end subsidies that benefit
cattle and sheep ranchers.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, which was approved 339-82, faces a veto threat
because of disputes with the Clinton administration over the level
of funding and some food safety and environmental issues.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton had requested $76.8 billion in spending for
the Agriculture Department and the Food and Drug Administration for
the 2001 budget, which begins Oct. 1. This year's budget, including
$8.7 billion in farm disaster assistance, was $84.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The House funding ''is woefully inadequate'' and ''does not meet
the needs'' of agriculture, said Wisconsin Rep. David Obey, senior
Democrat on the House Appropriations Committee. ''This bill has a
long way to go before it is going to receive a presidential
signature.''
</P>
<P>
   Not included in the House bill was $7.1 billion in special farm
assistance that Congress approved this spring to compensate growers
for depressed commodity prices.
</P>
<P>
   Before finishing work on the bill, the House defeated an effort
to end federal subsidies for killing coyotes, mountain lions and
other livestock predators and voted to preserve subsidies for wool
and mohair producers that were included in this spring's farm aid.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also would bar the FDA from discouraging Americans from
buying prescription drugs in Canada and other foreign countries.
Technically, it's illegal to import prescription drugs that were
originally made in the United States, and the Food and Drug
Administration sometimes sends warning letters to people caught
doing it.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers did drop from the bill a provision that would allow
for food and medicine sales to Cuba, but House Republican leaders
have agreed to try to put a more restricted version in the final
version of the legislation later this year.
</P>
<P>
   The House voted 228-190 to continue the predator-control
program, despite arguments by critics that it amounts to corporate
welfare for wealthy ranchers in the West.
</P>
<P>
   ''Why send a federal employee to take care of their interests?''
Rep. Peter DeFazio, D-Ore., asked in a debate that reflected the
House's urban-rural split.
</P>
<P>
   The Agriculture Department spends about $10 million a year
killing about 100,000 animals, mostly costly coyotes, but also
foxes, wolves and mountain lions.
</P>
<P>
   ''Maybe if we released some of these wolves in Portland,
Minneapolis, Boston or New York City we would have a different
attitude by members in this House,'' said Rep. Collin Peterson,
D-Minn.
</P>
<P>
   One of the bill's provisions that the Clinton administration
doesn't like would weaken egg testing regulations proposed by FDA.
The House left the measure in the bill but egg producers are
negotiating with the agency to alter its proposed testing
requirements.
</P>
<P>
   FDA has proposed to require that producers test for salmonella
enteritidis all around their farm, not just on the hens or eggs,
and to require that all of a farm's eggs be pasteurized or diverted
from market if the bacteria is found.
</P>
<P>
   ''The public would have been put at risk'' by the
industry-sponsored provision in the bill weakening the agency's
proposal, said Rep. Frank Pallone, D-N.J.
</P>
<P>
   The provision is to be stripped from the bill once the industry
and FDA reach a compromise. The compromise would still require the
testing but would not require that eggs be diverted from market
unless bacteria was actually found on one of them.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're all working together here to provide a safe,
higher-quality product,'' said Ken Klippen, a spokesman for the
United Egg Producers.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's plan, which also would require a warning
label for egg cartons, is supposed to reduce salmonella cases by
half in five years.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is to take up its version of the appropriations bill
later this month.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bill is H.R. 4461.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.house.gov/appropriations
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
