<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A defiant Whitman refuses to apologize for frisk photo  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERSEY CITY, N.J. (AP) - A defiant Gov. Christie Whitman refused
to apologize for searching an unarmed black man and issued a
warning to activists who plan to use a photograph of that pat-down
against her.
</P>
<P>
   ''Apologies are too easy,'' Whitman said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing at Ellis Island, Whitman vowed to stand by her reforms
of the State Police and her efforts to improve Camden, New Jersey's
poorest city.
</P>
<P>
   ''I will not be bullied away from that. I will not be scared
away from that commitment,'' Whitman said.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman also denied charges that state troopers were promised a
bounty of a one week vacation if they snapped a picture of the
governor with a black suspect.
</P>
<P>
   ''I certainly wasn't knowingly a participant in anything like
that and that certainly is an insult to imply that I was,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman repeatedly told reporters the search and the
four-year-old photograph have nothing to with racial profiling, the
practice where police target suspects based solely on race. Whitman
and her administration have been dogged by accusations that they
were insensitive to accusations by minority groups.
</P>
<P>
   ''In and of itself, that picture proves nothing,'' Whitman said.
</P>
<P>
   ''That picture doesn't say anything about racial profiling,''
she said. ''I saw how you can do good police work and not engage in
racial profiling. They targeted criminals.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Friday with The Associated Press, Whitman said
she was not sure if there is anything wrong with searching a man
who was never charged with a crime.
</P>
<P>
   The governor also said she did not know if she had the legal
authority to search someone. ''It never occurred to me to ask that
question,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman has said she did not think twice about searching the man
and was attempting to fully experience police work. At the time the
governor had been accompanying state troopers on night tours of
Camden, just months after the city logged a record number of
homicides.
</P>
<P>
   Now Whitman makes only one concession: She would put some
thought into a search of an unarmed, unnamed resident.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's a very legitimate thing to say, 'You should have
thought twice,''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A photograph obtained by the AP shows Whitman standing behind a
black man, his arms spread, palms pressed up against a wall.
</P>
<P>
   The governor is wearing jeans, a sweatshirt, a baseball cap and
black gloves and appears to be smiling.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have no idea what happened in that moment before'' the
picture was snapped, Whitman said. She said the photograph might
have captured either a smile or a grimace.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman said those who say the picture proves she encouraged
racial profiling are taking the image out of context.
</P>
<P>
   Now the governor admits the photograph can hurt both her image
and her work to revitalize Camden's economy.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no question about it. Damage can be done,'' she said.
''I can't prevent people from taking this picture and inflaming
people.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Al Sharpton, whose protest over racial profiling shut
down the Atlantic City Expressway last year, said he will meet
Thursday with members of the Black Ministers Council of New Jersey
to plan a new round of demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in Washington, D.C., Sharpton said he plans
a national rally Aug. 26 to protest racial profiling.
</P>
<P>
   The Whitman photograph will be featured at that demonstration
and others, Sharpton said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Clearly the picture of Gov. Whitman will be one we will show
the nation on how insensitive and in many ways how many governors
and other public officials are in denial about how they have not
only condoned, but in fact have tried to cover up the fact that
racial profiling has been a state-sanctioned strategy of law
enforcement,'' Sharpton said.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton said the picture could affect the political future of
Whitman, who has been mentioned as a possible vice presidential
candidate with George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ''A picture's worth a thousand words. It might be worth a vice
presidential nomination,'' Sharpton said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Clearly Mr. Bush needs to read his own speech yesterday to the
NAACP, and look at this photograph, and then he would have to
decide whether he could sell compassionate conservatism, reaching
out to blacks, and this photograph in the same speech. If he thinks
he can, I have a bridge in Brooklyn that he can sell.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
