<HEADLINE> Police arrest man in park robbery spree, but another robbery pattern emerges </HEADLINE>
By DONNA DE LA CRUZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - A day after police apprehended a man suspected
of robbing five women at gunpoint in Central Park, they began
investigating another string of robberies there by a group of young
men, authorities said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, two people were robbed within five minutes by a
group of four to five men near the park's famous Wollman Rink.
Robberies are up slightly this year in Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   At 10:50 p.m., a 47-year-old man riding his bicycle southbound
through the park near 63rd Street and Center Drive was knocked to
the ground by the men, police said. The suspects took $86 in cash,
a knife and sunglasses before fleeing. The victim, who suffered
bruises to his left arm, flagged down a police officer.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, a 30-year-old man told police he was
walking through the park near Wollman Rink when he was approached
by a group of men who knocked him to the ground, then took his
pager and $10.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's robberies occurred a day after police arrested Reinaldo
Joseph, 38, of Brooklyn, for allegedly robbing five women at
gunpoint in the park since April. Police arrested him after a
person playing checkers in the park saw a police sketch of the
robbery suspect and pointed Joseph out to officers on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   A mounted police officer and a scooter cop grabbed Joseph, who
was carrying a fake gun in his backpack, police said. The
authentic-looking pistol matched the description of the weapon used
in the robberies, said Assistant Chief William Taylor, head of
Manhattan detectives.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the five victims have picked Joseph out of a lineup,
Taylor said. The others were tourists who have since returned home.
Three of the attacks occurred on the park's West Drive, between
77th and 81st streets; one occurred near the Sheep Meadow; and one
on the park's East Drive, near 74th Street.
</P>
<P>
   The robberies occurred on April 6, April 28, May 11, June 22 and
July 7. All took place on either a Thursday or a Friday; most
occurred in the late afternoon or evening, but the last one
happened at 10:45 a.m. The victims were between 22 and 25 years old
and were alone.
</P>
<P>
   The latest police statistics show that through Sunday, there
have been 36 robberies in the park this year, compared with 27 the
same period last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
