<HEADLINE> SEC Workers Rally Before Union Vote  </HEADLINE>
By MARCY GORDON
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Employees sang a labor-organizing song in an
auditorium at the Securities and Exchange Commission two days
before a vote by agency workers on whether to join a union.
</P>
<P>
   The vote scheduled for Thursday has been opposed for months by
SEC officials, who wanted employees at the Washington headquarters
to be represented by a separate bargaining unit from those in the
agency's regional offices around the country.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute delayed a vote first scheduled for last September by
SEC employees on joining the National Treasury Employees Union,
which represents about 155,000 workers in 26 federal agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Labor Relations Authority ruled against the SEC in
January. The SEC appealed the ruling; its appeal was rejected this
spring.
</P>
<P>
   ''Finally, after all this talking about it, everyone's going to
get a chance to vote,'' Jeff Friday, national counsel for the NTEU,
told the few hundred employees gathered in the auditorium on their
lunch hour Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Workers listened and applauded as they balanced pizza provided
by the union on paper plates.
</P>
<P>
   Later, they joined in choruses of ''Union Members, Stand
Together,'' a song with new lyrics to the tune of an old-time labor
classic, ''Miner's Life.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Gulack and David Frye, who wrote the lyrics, led the
singing and played the guitar.
</P>
<P>
   ''Secretaries, paralegals and accountants join our cause! We
will bargain all together, just as we enforce the laws,'' went one
verse.
</P>
<P>
   The union needs to get a simple majority of votes cast to become
the SEC employees' official representative with management. NTEU
officials said they were confident, although there appears to be
far less support for the union among the SEC's 1,200 or so
professional employees, mainly attorneys and accountants, than by
the 650 other employees who are eligible to vote.
</P>
<P>
   The bitterness of the fight with the SEC was evident as Friday
cited employees' grievances. Chief among them: a series of
''informational meetings'' on the union issue organized by SEC
management for employees.
</P>
<P>
   SEC officials have defended the meetings as being legal and a
useful way to provide information to employees.
</P>
<P>
   ''We think they've been very fruitful,'' SEC spokesman Chris
Ullman said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Union officials also complained about the SEC using public money
to retain a law firm they said was actively anti-union.
</P>
<P>
   Ullman said the agency ''felt it was in the best interest of
employees to have labor lawyers guiding us through this process,''
since attorneys at the SEC -- which regulates the nation's
securities markets and mutual funds -- don't have expertise in labor
law.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have every intention of abiding by the results of the
election,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Employees also have complained that they are expected to work
uncompensated extra hours, known as ''donated'' time, and that
bonus money is seldom given to career employees.
</P>
<P>
   In brief remarks, NTEU President Colleen Kelley said the
election will give SEC employees a chance ''to be part of a driving
force of change.''
</P>
<P>
   The NTEU represents employees at the Internal Revenue Service,
the U.S. Customs Service, the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. and
the Food and Drug Administration, among others.
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   National Treasury Employees Union: http://www.nteu.org
</P>
<P>
   Securities and Exchange Commission: http://www.sec.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-11-00 1747 </TRAILER>
