<BODY>
<HEADLINE> In 'Dancing Demons,' wonderfully scary Mongolian masks make U.S. debut </HEADLINE>
By KATHERINE ROTH
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Bulging eyeballs and skull tiaras. Wagging red
tongues and big floppy ears. Flashing mirrors and ringing bells.
Faces in lumpy red or greenish gold. Sometimes it takes a little
extra to chase away demons and conjure better luck. And some times
it takes a lot.
</P>
<P>
   In traditional Mongolia, which boasts a no-holds-barred approach
to the matter, the latter seems to be the case. The exhibit
''Dancing Demons: Ceremonial Masks of Mongolia'' displays the
fabulous - and rare - dance masks in all their splendor at the Asia
Society starting Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Buried or hidden in trunks during the decades when they were
banned in a Mongolia under Communist rule, the startling masks and
costumes are finally seeing the light in the nation of nomads and
tundra between China and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The annual ''Tsam'' dances, in which a series of dancers dressed
as demon deities or in fantastic animal heads to exorcise evil
spirits, were held last year in Mongolia for the first time since
about 1937, said Jan Fontein, curator of the show. Old photographs,
paintings and the fading memories of those who participated decades
ago are helping Mongolians revive the tradition.
</P>
<P>
   The masks and other artifacts are being displayed for the first
time in the United States, said Fontein, a noted Asian art scholar
and former director of the Museum of Fine Arts in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're very wrathful figures, very bloodthirsty,
blood-drinking demons,'' said Fontein, describing the deities which
came to Mongolia with the introduction of Tibetan Buddhism in the
17th century. Buddhism was combined with shamanism, the traditional
belief system of the Mongolian nomads.
</P>
<P>
   The over 60 artifacts, most from the 18th and 19th centuries,
represent about a third of the objects featured in a recent major
exhibit at the Nieuwe Kerk Museum in Amsterdam. They will be on
view at the Park Avenue gallery through Sept. 17, after which they
return to Mongolia.
</P>
<P>
   Among the very rare objects featured is perhaps the finest of
only three known Mongolian ancestral figures in existence. The 19th
century figure of a bearded man carved of birchwood with a horse
hair beard was used by Mongolian shamans, or witchdoctors, to ward
away evil. The figure's face is still greasy from years of being
smeared with fat as part of traditional rituals.
</P>
<P>
   There are also drums and costumes used by Mongolian shamans
featuring mirrors, bells, and eagle and owl feathers.
</P>
<P>
   But the most breathtaking pieces are the bright papier-mache
masks, which are displayed in the order in which the figures appear
in the Tsam dances. Most are accompanied by photos from the 1930s
showing them being used in the dances.
</P>
<P>
   Two frightening human skull masks, each with a tiara of five
smaller skulls, dance solemnly to start the massive exorcism
ritual. They are among the very few still in existence, Fontein
said.
</P>
<P>
   Later, one of the most striking masks appears. With the
cartoonish face of an old Mongolian man, the character known as the
White Old Man has a wrinkled face and a bushy white beard made of
horse hair and cotton. He represents the shamanistic gods of
Mongolia which were absorbed into the Buddhist pantheon. Armed with
a staff featuring a dragon-shaped handle, he performed the role of
the buffoon in the dance.
</P>
<P>
   Later there's a mask with three bulging eyeballs, a lumpy red
face made of coral and a five-skull tiara. Another has the
green-gold face of another horrible deity, also with three big
bulging eyes and a skull-tiara.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's a relatively harmless-looking deer mask with a
leopard-spot face and a wagging tongue made of red silk filled with
millet grains. But the deer, known as Shava, is supposed to be one
of the henchmen of Yama, the Supreme Judge of Hell.
</P>
<P>
   Yama finally shows his wonderfully scary face as the dramatic
finale of the Tsam - and of the exhibit. He has an azure bull's
head with blood red lips, bulging eyes and green-blue horns
decorated with swirling gold clouds or dragons.
</P>
<P>
   ''The bull is the grand finale, and then the evil is finally
exorcised,'' Fontein said.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: www.asiasociety.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-11-00 1748 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000711.0130 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Gains 81; Nasdaq Falls 24  </HEADLINE>
By SETH SUTEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Old Economy stocks came out on top Tuesday as
two stalwarts of traditional businesses -- paper and aluminum -- led
the market higher, with a little help from an upbeat speech from
Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan. Tech stocks continued a
modest decline.
</P>
<P>
   With the second-quarter earnings season just getting under way,
strong showings from International Paper on Tuesday and Alcoa the
day before helped bring old-fashioned brick and mortar companies
back into fashion with investors.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average, of which Alcoa and IP are both
components, rose 80.61 to 10,727.19. Financial, energy and basic
materials shares also rose.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's another day of triumph of the Old Economy over the New
Economy, prompted by International Paper's better-than-expected
earnings announcement,'' said Ronald J. Hill, investment strategist
at Brown Brothers Harriman &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index fell 23.87 to 3,956.42 as tech stocks
pulled back from a rally earlier in the day. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index rose 5.26 to 1,480.88.
</P>
<P>
   The strong earnings reports from IP and Alcoa helped lift other
makers of basic materials, including chemical producer DuPont, up
$2.375 at $47.313; Exxon Mobil, up $2.50 at $80.625; and oil
equipment maker Schlumberger, up $6.078 at $74.953.
</P>
<P>
   IP rose $3.312 to $35.25 after reporting its second-quarter
earnings per share beat analyst estimates by 1 cent. And Alcoa rose
$2.437 to $32.125 after it came out with better-than-expected
earnings on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan, meanwhile, told the National Governors' Association
that the explosion in the use of computers and other high-tech
devices has boosted America's productivity, the amount of output
for each hour of work. Increased productivity has been a primary
contributor to the nation's long economic expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Investors responded well to Greenspan's remarks, taking them as
a hint that the Fed might not raise rates at its next meeting in
August. Analysts have been split over whether the Fed has finished
raising rates for now, following its six increases over the past
year.
</P>
<P>
   But with more indications that the economy has been cooling,
investors have been growing more optimistic that the Fed will
determine that rates are currently high enough to contain
inflationary pressures.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a market conviction that the Fed may be taking its foot
off the brakes,'' said Tom Galvin, chief equity straegist at
Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette Securities. ''The lack of any strong
talk out of Greenspan added further conviction that the days of
credit tightening are limited.''
</P>
<P>
   Shares of financial companies, which are among the first to
benefit from steady interest rates, rose following Greenspan's
remarks. Chase Manhattan rose 93.8 cents to $50.688, and home
mortgage reseller Fannie Mae rose $1.313 to $58.688.
</P>
<P>
   High-tech stocks that fell on Monday tried to rally early in
Tuesday's session, but then faltered.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo! shares slumped $4.50 to $105.50. The Internet bellwether
released strong earnings after the market closed, beating analyst
expectations by 2 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Other Internet companies followed Yahoo! lower, including
America Online, down 75 cents at $55, and Amazon.com, down $1.938
at $33.125.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues edged ahead of declining issues by a 5-to-4
margin on the New York Stock Exchange, where composite volume came
to 1.18 billion shares, up slightly from the day before.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index fell 1.09 to 529.74.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.4 percent.
Germany's DAX index was fell 0.9 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 was
up 0.1 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up 0.04 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
