<HEADLINE> Israelis Rally, Protest, Fast  </HEADLINE>
By JOCELYN NOVECK
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Just as the Camp David summit got under way
Tuesday, so did the campaign back home for the hearts and minds of
two peoples.
</P>
<P>
   Orthodox Jews, secular Israeli families, West Bank settlers,
Palestinian refugees and army generals were among those attending
rallies, staging hunger strikes or finding other ways to voice
their feelings.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Ehud Barak weighed in from afar. Israelis awoke
to a front-page letter from the embattled leader in the top-selling
Yediot Ahronot newspaper, appealing to their imaginations with a
vision of an Israel no longer in conflict with Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   After the embarrassing political debacle he suffered just before
his departure, Barak would have been heartened to see the evening
rush-hour in downtown Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic was diverted and streets were blocked off near the prime
minister's residence for a festive rally supporting Barak and his
peace initiatives. A crowd of several thousand listened to peace
songs and plastered themselves with stickers saying: ''The Majority
Has Chosen Peace -- Me Too!''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Morin, a 70-year-old retired professor, said the last
time he'd attended a rally was the huge gathering at which the late
Yitzhak Rabin was assassinated in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ''But these are special times,'' said Morin, who leaned on a
walking stick and sported a specially made T-shirt that said
''Shalom (Peace) -- Just Do It.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I truly believe that 60 percent of Israelis are for peace at
Camp David. But in the streets, all you hear is the voice of the
right,'' he said, echoing the fears of Barak himself.
</P>
<P>
   David Breski, a 23-year-old student, agreed. ''What you saw in
the government the past two days does not represent what people
think,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Barak left Israel Monday after enduring a humiliating
no-confidence vote in parliament that he barely survived. A day
earlier, he was deserted by three right-wing coalition parties
fearing concessions he'd make to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   The right wing also made its voice heard Tuesday. Thousands of
Orthodox Jews gathered at Judaism's holiest site, the Western Wall,
to pray and to hand out leaflets saying: ''Barak is losing the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those bitterly opposing the Camp David summit are settlers
in the West Bank and Gaza Strip, who fear they'll be forced to
leave their homes in what they regard as the biblical land of
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Nurit Ben Porath, from the Kedumim settlement in the central
West Bank, attended the protest with her five small children. ''We
want God to save us from Barak,'' she said. ''He wants to give us
to the Arabs.''
</P>
<P>
   About 30 settlers also gathered at noontime at a park near
Barak's office and began a hunger strike, which they said would
last through the summit.
</P>
<P>
   In the Balata refugee camp near Nablus, dozens of Palestinian
youngsters were joined by armed men with masked faces as they
marched on behalf of refugee rights.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want to say to the Palestinian delegation, don't forget the
refugees' rights,'' said Hussam Khader, one of the organizers.
''Anybody who will harm our rights, he deserves a bullet in his
heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Demonstrating in their own way were 28 retired Israeli army
generals, who wrote in a paid advertisement: ''Go in peace, Ehud
Barak.''
</P>
<P>
   In his own letter, Barak envisioned an Israel with no
Palestinian conflict to worry about.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will be able to focus on the things that are more important
than anything,'' he wrote. ''A better education for our children,
renewed growth in the economy, investment in infrastructure and the
creation of jobs, the allocation of our resources to health,
welfare, the closing of the social gaps.''
</P>
<P>
   As tantalizing as that sounded to many, the irony was surely not
lost. Those are precisely the issues that critics have accused
Barak of neglecting in the year since he took office, all in the
name of pursuing peace.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
