<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NTSB Urges Immediate 911 Calls  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal investigators, probing a natural gas
explosion that killed four people in St. Cloud, Minn., two years
ago, said lives could have been saved had workers who severed the
line been under orders to call 911 immediately.
</P>
<P>
   The National Transportation Safety Board urged a national,
industrywide effort to ensure that excavators immediately call 911
or other local emergency response numbers if they know an
underground gas line has been damaged.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Hall, the safety board chairman, said the threat of gas
explosions is growing in virtually every community in the nation as
crews dig alongside gas pipes for a wide variety of reasons,
including the installation of fiber optic cable used in high-tech
communications systems.
</P>
<P>
   ''This goes on every day; it is a constant challenge that we
have; it can be a real danger and a threat,'' Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   The St. Cloud explosion on Dec. 11, 1998 killed four people,
injured 11 and destroyed six buildings.
</P>
<P>
   The blast occurred about 40 minutes after a construction crew,
attempting to install a support for a utility pole, ruptured an
underground, one-inch plastic gas service pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   The board ruled that the probable cause of the accident was the
lack of proper procedures by Cable Constructors Inc. to prevent
damage to nearby gas lines after it encountered unusual conditions
underground.
</P>
<P>
   Safety board investigators said that although the gas line had
been properly located and marked, the accident occurred when the
work crew hit an underground granite slab, bending their drilling
equipment and severing the line.
</P>
<P>
   The board said that the explosion might have been prevented and
lives might have been saved had the foreman of the work crew been
under orders to immediately call 911 or other emergency numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they said, there was a half-hour delay in notifying the
local gas company and local fire and police agencies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-11-00 1804 </TRAILER>
