<DOCNO> APW20000711.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mideast Summit Notebook  </HEADLINE>
By LAURA KING
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. (AP) -- You first! No, you! No, I insist -- you!
</P>
<P>
   Opening the Middle East summit on a jocular note, Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat staged a
mock wrestling match as they tried to usher each other into their
first joint meeting with President Clinton at Camp David.
</P>
<P>
   Both leaders grinned broadly and the ends of Arafat's checkered
keffiyeh headdress flew as the two playfully muscled one another
toward the door after Clinton had entered. In the end, Arafat went
first.
</P>
<P>
   The clowning stands in sharp contrast to what are expected to be
some tense moments behind closed doors during the summit. Both
sides have said any compromises would be difficult and painful.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   If they get a craving for a midnight snack, Arafat and Barak
won't run into each another in the kitchen. The two leaders are
staying in separate cabins at Camp David.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean there won't be opportunities for informal
encounters. The rustic presidential retreat has plenty of wooded
walking trails, a putting green and even a bowling alley. And the
White House hasn't ruled out a sightseeing trip to break summit
tensions.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Buddy is acquiring some serious diplomatic credentials.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton brought his dog with him to Camp David for the
summit opening. Buddy, a chocolate Labrador, looked eager to
travel; he bounded across the White House lawn and up the chopper
steps ahead of his master.
</P>
<P>
   Buddy also accompanied Clinton to the Israeli-Palestinian summit
at Wye River two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Just don't call it quaint.
</P>
<P>
   Thurmont, Md., the nearest community to Camp David, may have
plenty of small-town trappings: fireflies, cornfields, people
whiling away hot summer evenings on their porch swings.
</P>
<P>
   But don't make too much of that bucolic atmosphere, admonished
the daily newspaper serving the town. The Frederick Post, out of
nearby Frederick, Md., observed acerbically in an editorial that
summit visitors were probably working overtime to ''find variations
of 'quaint''' to describe Thurmont.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean, though, that locals weren't eager to offer
the participants their good wishes.
</P>
<P>
   ''Welcome, Bill, Ehud and Yasser,'' said a sign in the window of
Holly's Country Florist on Main Street. ''Think peace.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Middle East leaders? Presidents? Historic peace talks? Margaret
Krone has seen it all before.
</P>
<P>
   Now 85 and retired, she was Thurmont's town librarian during the
Camp David summit of 1978, when then-President Jimmy Carter held
landmark talks with Egypt's Anwar Sadat and Israel's Menachem
Begin.
</P>
<P>
   Krone, who is working this week as a volunteer in the summit
media center, recalled that when Carter took his guests to see the
nearby battlefield at Gettysburg, Pa., journalists flocked to her
library to bone up on Civil War history.
</P>
<P>
   ''This time around, I expect they'd just get on the Internet,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   If there's one thing Israelis and Palestinians have in common,
it's their love of talking nonstop on their cellular phones.
</P>
<P>
   But as at past peace summits, delegation sources on both sides
said the Americans had asked them not to use their mobile phones at
Camp David. The idea is that solitude and privacy might help
produce a breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart deflected a question about
the ban, saying he wasn't aware of it. But he said the point was
moot because of cell phone service problems in the rugged Catoctin
Mountains, where Camp David is located.
</P>
<P>
   ''They don't work,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   With much of their school commandeered as a center for the
international press corps covering the summit, kids attending the
summer session at Thurmont Elementary got a few impromptu lessons
in diplomacy and foreign affairs.
</P>
<P>
   And gave a few as well.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're here to talk about peace and fix their problems so
they don't have to keep having wars,'' explained 9-year-old Chris
Schildt, bouncing a basketball. ''Do you want to know anything
else?''
</P>
<P>
   More than 300 reporters covering the summit worked in makeshift
pressrooms surrounded by chalkboards, kids' crayon drawings and
alphabet charts. The tables and chairs were adult-sized, though.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Figuring it was the closest they'd get to the leaders conferring
at Camp David, a few dozen demonstrators gathered outside the media
center as the summit was beginning, singing songs and waving
banners.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wanted to get out and show my support for what Mr. Barak is
trying to do,'' said 75-year-old Sam Green of Washington D.C., who
wore a bumper sticker reading ''Peace Now'' plastered across his
forehead.
</P>
<P>
   Later, protesters opposing concessions to the Palestinians also
turned out, chanting ''Jerusalem is Jewish'' and displaying signs
saying ''Barak is a traitor.'' A few got in shouting matches with
demonstrators from the peace camp.
</P>
<P>
   ''We can't abide this so-called peace process,'' said Levi
Huebner of New York, who holds Israeli citizenship. ''We can't
stand by and watch him (Barak) endanger our brothers.''
</P>
<P>
   Some demonstrators needed a little help puzzling out their own
Hebrew-language signs.
</P>
<P>
   ''Oh, yeah,'' said Suzanne Davidson of Washington. ''It says,
'Israel wants peace.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-11-00 1804 </TRAILER>
