<HEADLINE> Ads May Fuel Public Education Fight  </HEADLINE>
By ANJETTA McQUEEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Wall Street investor is spending about $20
million of his own money on election-season TV ads to tell parents
''America's government-run public school monopoly is failing our
children.''
</P>
<P>
   Ted Forstmann, known for giving away millions in private school
scholarships himself, insisted Tuesday that he's not asking parents
to pressure lawmakers to spend public money on tuition vouchers --
or to push them over charter schools or any other alternative to
traditional public schools.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's not what we're talking about at all,'' said Forstmann,
who showed two 15-second spot television commercials in a news
conference. ''What I want is for parents to be aware of the facts
and the possibilities and say yes, 'we want to be in charge.' . . .
And we'll figure out what to do from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Vouchers, publicly funded certificates that parents and children
can use at a private or parochial school, have gained ground as
communities grow frustrated with low test scores and student
performance. But vouchers also have fueled the election-year debate
over the track record of public education.
</P>
<P>
   Public education supporters were especially critical of the ad
campaign, whose backers include former Atlanta Mayor Andrew Young,
a Democrat; Martin Luther King III; and Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mr. Forstmann and others refuse to use the word 'vouchers' but
it's clearly what they are suggesting,'' said Kathleen Lyons,
spokeswoman for the National Education Association, the larger
teachers' union, with 2&AMP;frac12; million members.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think it's positive to systematically downgrade and
demonize public schools; a person who has a public voice ought to
be using that voice to improve public education,'' Education
Secretary Richard Riley said when asked about the ads after
addressing a group of private educators here.
</P>
<P>
   One of the spots, which will run nationally on cable and network
television from next week until the end of the year, features a
schoolroom with kids throwing paper airplanes and horsing around as
a teacher tries to restore order.
</P>
<P>
   The voiceover begins by saying schools are failing students.
''One in three kids will not graduate with their classmates. And
parents feel powerless,'' it adds.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers are shown the address of the group's Web site, which
will gauge, not dictate, parents' interests and concerns, said Dan
Schnur, executive director of Forstmann's Campaign for America's
Children.
</P>
<P>
   Forstmann, along with Wal-Mart fortune heir John Walton, last
year gave 40,000 children nationwide $1,300 partial private-school
scholarships. Forstmann said the response to the scholarship
lottery -- some 1.2 million families -- prompted the current
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign is nonpartisan and not endorsing candidates, he
said. Vice President Al Gore and his presidential rival, Texas Gov.
George Bush, have yet to accept an invitation from the group to a
debate solely on education.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the Republican, has proposed using public funds to help
poor children in failing schools attend better public or private
campuses. Democrat Gore is against public funding of private
schools. He's won endorsement from the two major teachers' unions
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Campaign for America's Children:
www.parentsincharge.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
