<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anti-toll group pushes lawmakers to get rid of Parkway toll booths  </HEADLINE>
By WAYNE PARRY
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - An anti-toll group is pursuing what has long
been a fantasy for many New Jersey motorists: eliminating toll
booths on the Garden State Parkway.
</P>
<P>
   But the group's solution for the lost revenue such a move would
entail might not go over so well with the motoring public at a time
when unleaded regular gasoline costs nearly $1.60 a gallon:
increasing the state's gasoline tax by 3 cents a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Citizens Against Tolls says it has gotten thousands
of signatures on petitions it plans to present to Gov. Christie
Whitman. On Tuesday, they enlisted the support of Jersey City Mayor
Bret Schundler, who was to appear with them at an evening rally in
Woodbridge.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're concerned that we have this organization of hundreds of
people just to collect tolls, with 93 buildings, people to care for
those buildings, and managers making over $100,000 a year,'' said
Ray Neveil, a retired phone company manager from Brielle who
founded the group last fall. ''They're a needless, make-work
operation. These tolls cause traffic jams, air pollution, wasted
fuel, and economic loss.''
</P>
<P>
   Neveil says it's a lot less onerous to increase the gasoline tax
and have unimpeded traffic flow on one of the state's most heavily
traveled roads. He calculates that a 3-cent increase would offset
the cost of having the state Department of Transportation maintain
the Parkway.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's an interesting idea, but a very complicated one, and
would require an act of the legislature,'' said Laura Otterbourg, a
spokeswoman for Whitman. ''The governor would consider it if the
legislature were to put forth a proposal.''
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Ingoglia, a spokesman for the New Jersey Highway
Authority, which operates the 173-mile toll road, said the Parkway
still has to be funded, regardless of where the money comes from.
</P>
<P>
   ''The removal of tolls is a legitimate public question, and the
discussion deserves all the facts,'' he said. ''You can eliminate
tolls, but you cannot eliminate the things tolls pay for: snow
removal, State Police patrols, roadway maintenance. All those
things still have to be paid for. Do you want to do it by charging
the people who use the roadway, or through taxes from people
whether they use it or not?''
</P>
<P>
   Ingoglia noted that 1 in 5 vehicles that uses the Parkway is
from out of state, a figure that increases to 1 in 4 during the
summer. He also disputed figures presented by Citizens Against
Tolls claiming that it costs 13 cents of every 35-cent toll just to
pay for collection. The real figure is 7 cents, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Schundler, who has his own grass-roots anti-tax group, Empower
The People, said he supports the goal of removing the toll plazas,
but not hiking the gasoline tax.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe there's a strong consensus to remove the tolls,'' he
said. ''As far as how to fund roadways, that's a discussion we can
have another day.''
</P>
<P>
   Schundler called Parkway tolls a hidden tax.
</P>
<P>
   ''Not only is it a financial tax, it's a tax on people's
lives,'' he said. ''It wastes work time and family time and causes
enormous mental aggravation.''
</P>
<P>
   He recalled an incident when he was in college where he was
sitting in a long line of cars approaching Parkway toll booths, and
someone tried to cut in front of him.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was one of those situations where because you've been there
so long you just don't want to let anyone get in front of you,'' he
said. ''We ended up in a situation where our front bumpers were in
contact, but neither of us was going even a tenth of a mile an
hour, so there was no damage.
</P>
<P>
   ''This guy had a nice car, and I had an old beat-up type of car
you'd expect a college student to have, and suddenly the other guy
started opening his door and pounding my passenger door,''
Schundler said. ''So I rolled down my window and yelled, 'Do it
some more!' The point is the whole thing should never have happened
if we didn't have tolls.''
</P>
<P>
   The call for a toll-free Parkway by the citizens group is not
the first. Last summer, two Morris County legislators, state Sen.
Robert Martin and Assembly Transportation Committee Chairman Alex
DeCroce, floated a proposal to eliminate eight of the highway's 11
toll plazas while increasing the remaining tolls to $1. But they
later backed off that proposal, saying the Parkway should upgrade
E-ZPass to enable cars to go through faster than the 5 mph now
required. Such technology is still considered to be years away.
</P>
<P>
 On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.endtolls.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www.gspkwy.state.nj.us
</P>
</TEXT>
