<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Supremes' Tour Future Uncertain  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- So who exactly is going to sing ''Baby Love''
and ''Where Did Our Love Go'' for the rest of this summer, if
anyone?
</P>
<P>
   Confusion swirled around the ill-fated Diana Ross &AMP; The Supremes
reunion tour on Tuesday, a day after Ross said her promoter had
canceled the tour. The promoter, SFX, announced that a concert set
for Wednesday in Hartford, Conn., had been called off but insisted
it had not pulled the plug on the rest of the tour.
</P>
<P>
   Only about 1,400 of some 10,000 available tickets had been sold
for the Hartford show, said Joe Flanagan, marketing director for
the Hartford Civic Center. Prices had ranged up to $250.
</P>
<P>
   A Ross spokesman, Paul Bloch, said Tuesday that Ross stands by
her statement that the tour has been canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if there's still a chance that Ross will sing on any of
the upcoming dates, Bloch said ''I've been given no indication that
there's a possibility of that at all.''
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, local representatives said they expected Thursday's
show to go on.
</P>
<P>
   ''We haven't received definitive word from the promoter yet as
far as any cancellation,'' Jim Delaney, a spokesman for the
FleetCenter in Boston, said. ''As of right now we have to go on the
assumption that the show is still happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Industry insiders suggested the confusion may be a prelude to
legal maneuvering over how much money SFX is required to pay Ross,
if any, for the canceled dates of the tour.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
