<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mother complains about kids on Senate mail list  </HEADLINE>
By BETH J. HARPAZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - A Bay Shore mother is complaining that her
children received Senate fund-raising letters after she provided
their names and addresses for a security check prior to meeting
Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Savino had been invited to a reception with Clinton at Bay
Shore High School Sept. 8 and was allowed to bring her three young
children. She provided their names and Social Security numbers for
security purposes for ''a first lady visiting our school.''
</P>
<P>
   In the following months, she and the children received
individual White House Christmas cards, followed by fund-raising
letters.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't like to be used. I don't like to be duped,'' Savino
said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's spokesman, Howard Wolfson, said Tuesday that the
meeting was a campaign event and that the participants' names were
collected by the campaign, for use by the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Savino said she was under the impression that Clinton had been
visiting as a first lady. But Clinton's Senate campaign staff
accompanied her to the high school and drove a van carrying
reporters from Manhattan. Clinton also held a news conference that
day about Senate issues.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Gross, a Washington, D.C., lawyer who formerly worked
for the Federal Elections Commission, said that if costs associated
with the event were paid for by the Clinton campaign rather than
the federal government, ''then names accumulated are fair game.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Secret Service, Jim Mackin, said: ''On
occasion we do name checks for certain events. When we do that, we
share that information with no one.''
</P>
<P>
   The state Assembly minority leader, John Faso, agreed with
Savino.
</P>
<P>
   ''That is inappropriate,'' said Faso, a supporter of Clinton's
GOP Senate opponent, Rep. Rick Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   ''One wonders how many other times have they done this,'' Faso
said Tuesday on WROW-AM radio in Albany. ''Here's this first lady
out there saying how she wants to protect everyone's privacy. The
first thing they do is they trample on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton herself has been an advocate for greater privacy
protections.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't believe you should give up your privacy when you visit
your doctor, take a trip to the video store or buy a book on the
Internet,'' she said last month.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Kelly, head of the Bay Shore Board of Education, did not
immediately return calls seeking comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
