<HEADLINE> Olympic Officer Expects Lower Costs  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- The 2002 Winter Games won't be as
expensive as expected.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a month after stepping down as president of the Utah
senate to monitor Olympic finances, State Olympic officer Lane
Beattie said Monday that state agencies won't need nearly as much
money as originally estimated to cover expenses for the games in
Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   Just how much less is still being calculated, the Deseret News
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Beattie said the figures would be released in about two weeks,
in his inaugural report on the financial impact the Olympics will
have on Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Beattie was appointed State Olympic officer in June by Gov. Mike
Leavitt. Months earlier, Beattie announced he would not run for
re-election in the Senate, where he has served since 1989.
</P>
<P>
   The Olympics are costing SLOC nearly $1.32 billion, not
including government costs for public safety and other expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's report from former Olympic officer John Fowler
estimated the Legislature would need to find $31 million for
everything from paying police overtime to building new roads.
</P>
<P>
   The SLOC devised a plan to raise $15 million toward the cost of
providing protection to the public during the Games.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers came up with $2 million and lawmakers agreed not to
tax Olympic tickets, freeing another $13 million. Other savings are
possible as state agencies review expected expenses through the
games and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   Beattie worries about public safety and transportation.
</P>
<P>
   ''Those are two issues that could destroy the success of an
Olympics very quickly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A meeting with state agencies to take a look at ''everything
from life to death, meaning emergency preparedness ... down to
Olympic pins'' will likely be held in the next two to three weeks,
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
