<HEADLINE> Ousted Atlantic City councilwoman gives up on challenge  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CURRAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) - The former president of the City
Council said Tuesday she would withdraw a civil suit challenging
the results of the election that ousted her from office.
</P>
<P>
   Rosalind Norrell-Nance, 50, said she could not afford to pursue
the challenge any longer. But she called on the county prosecutor
to investigate allegations that her opponent's supporters cast
ballots on behalf of absentee voters in the June 13 run-off
election for her Second Ward seat.
</P>
<P>
   She said her complaints were not sour grapes over her loss to
political newcomer Robert L. Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ''Something has to be done about this,'' she said. ''If not,
we're going to find every election a total mess, with people using
these kinds of procedures to undercut the voters' choices.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, 43, defeated the two-term incumbent 574-515.
Norrell-Nance won at the polls but lost after Johnson supporter
David Callaway, acting as a messenger, hand-delivered 115 absentee
ballots to the Board of Elections.
</P>
<P>
   Among those ballots, 112 voted for Johnson and three for
Norrell-Nance.
</P>
<P>
   Norrell-Nance said an investigator working for her had
identified 91 instances of election fraud, several involving
Callaway and his brother, Craig Callaway.
</P>
<P>
   The two told voters there was an easier way to vote than going
to the polls, and asked voters to sign a document, Norrell-Nance
said. The voters told the investigator later that they never marked
the yellow absentee ballots used in the election, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The investigator also found that residents of Pleasantville,
Mays Landing and other Atlantic City wards voted in the election,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Superior Court Judge Michael Winkelstein rejected
Norrell-Nance's request for an investigation by the Board of
Elections on June 29, saying the burden of proof was
Norrell-Nance's.
</P>
<P>
   But it would cost between $60,000 and $110,000 in attorney's
fees to take depositions, issue subpoenas and continue
investigating each vote. She wouldn't say how much she had spent to
date on the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ''She lost, we won. She got beat,'' said Daniel Perskie,
Johnson's lawyer. ''Her concessions don't sound like concessions,
but the bottom line is she's withdrawing her complaint.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither of the Callaways could be reached for comment. Craig
Callaway's home telephone rang unanswered Tuesday afternoon; there
was no listing for David Callaway's telephone, and Perskie said he
knew of no way to reach him.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said his supporters did nothing wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's Mrs. Nance's constitutional right to pursue any type of
matter she sees fit. Everything was fair and square,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantic County Prosecutor Jeffrey Blitz said he would review
Norrell-Nance's claims.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will review whatever information and data is submitted,
then make a decision regarding investigation,'' Blitz said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
