<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GAO Account Fuels Nuke Secret Fury  </HEADLINE>
By H. JOSEF HEBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- For 12 years, Energy Department procedures
have not required classified documents to be signed in and out by
users, a congressional investigator told lawmakers Tuesday. The
finding adds to their fury over how two computer drives containing
nuclear secrets went missing from the Los Alamos weapons lab last
month.
</P>
<P>
   An investigator for the General Accounting office told the House
Commerce Committee that the since 1988, and likely even before
that, the Energy Department ''has not and does not require a
sign-out sheet'' for secret or even top secret material.
</P>
<P>
   Other requirements for protecting and controlling secrets have
been discontinued, said Jim Wells, the GAO investigator. For
example, the lab no longer requires frequent inventories or unique
identification numbers for classified material, which makes it
easier to track.
</P>
<P>
   Since the discovery that the two disk drives had vanished from a
top-security vault for about two months at the Los Alamos lab in
New Mexico, some members of Congress have been dumbfounded to learn
that those using the drives weren't required to sign them out.
</P>
<P>
   At a hearing last month, Rep. Bart Stupak, D-Mich., wondered why
his hometown library has sign-out requirements for books, but the
weapons lab doesn't have any for nuclear secrets.
</P>
<P>
   Wells said the General Accounting Office reviewed changes that
have been made since 1988 for the control of classified material,
including secret and top secret nuclear weapons material.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988 ''complete accountability was required,'' said Wells,
but even then there was no sign-out or sign-in requirement for
secrets kept in areas where access was highly controlled such as
Los Alamos' ''X Division'' complex where nuclear weapons designers
worked.
</P>
<P>
   The two hard drives were last seen in the vault within the ''X
Division'' sometime in late March and discovered missing in early
May, but their disappearance was not reported for another three
weeks. They were found June 16 behind a copying machine not far
from the vault. The incident remains under FBI criminal
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO found that many requirements for protecting and
controlling secret and top secret material were discontinued during
the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   The policy revisions in 1992 and 1993 left ''a security system
that has deep flaws,'' said Rep. Tom Bliley, R-Va., the Commerce
Committee chairman. He added that the lack of such records
apparently has never been a violation of Energy Department security
rules.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-11-00 1849 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
