<HEADLINE> HUD HQ Named for Black Cabinet Head  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The headquarters of the Department of Housing
and Urban Development was named on Tuesday after Robert C. Weaver,
who became the nation's first black cabinet head when he was named
HUD secretary in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ''Robert Weaver was a pioneer who broke through bariers of
racism again and again to build a life of extraordinary achievement
and public service,'' HUD's current secretary Andrew Cuomo said
Tuesday. Cuomo was joined by Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan and Rep.
Charles Rangel, both New York Democrats, in naming the towering HUD
building in downtown Washington after Weaver.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Washington D.C. and a graduate of Harvard University,
Weaver played an active role in the civil rights movement. He also
served for a time in the administration of President Franklin
Delano Roosevelt working in the Department of Interior.
</P>
<P>
   In 1955, Weaver became deputy New York state rent commissioner,
later becoming the first black in the state's cabinet when he was
named commissioner. In 1959, he became vice-chairman of the New
York City Housing and Development Board. Soon after President John
F. Kennedy named him director of the federal Housing and Home
Finance Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy tried to have the agency raised to a cabinet rank but
Congress balked, led by southerners opposed to the appointment of a
black as a cabinet head.
</P>
<P>
   When President Lyndon Johnson succeeded in creating the
Department of Housing and Urban Development he appointed Weaver
secretary in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   Weaver moved back to New York City after his four-year term at
HUD, serving as president of Baruch College and professor of urban
affairs at Hunter College. He died in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-11-00 1856 </TRAILER>
