<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former bank employee sentenced to two weeks in prison  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - A former Bank of New York employee was sentenced
Tuesday to two weeks in prison and five and a half months home
confinement for her role in a $7 billion Russian money laundering
scam.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Jed S. Rakoff sentenced Svetlana
Kudryavtsev, 50, to prison even though prosecutors and a defense
lawyer conceded they mistakenly believed she had pleaded guilty to
a charge that did not carry a prison term.
</P>
<P>
   Rakoff said the prison term, however brief, was necessary to
''send a message that if you commit a crime of this sort, you will
go to jail.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal sentencing guidelines called for the Brooklyn woman to
receive at least a month in prison, but Rakoff said the facts of
the case were unusual enough to spare her a more serious sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Kudryavtsev had pleaded guilty to accepting illegal payments as
a bank employee and lying to investigators after accepting $500 a
month from Lucy Edwards and her husband to monitor bank accounts
which were being used to launder money.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, the bank's former vice president in the Eastern
European Division, has pleaded guilty to federal charges along with
her husband, Peter Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   ''I swear I didn't know Lucy was doing anything improper while
she was working at the bank,'' Kudryavtsev said through an
interpreter just before she was sentenced.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm really very, very sorry,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Her lawyer, Charles D. Adler, said his client had become close
friends of Edwards when they lived in Leningrad together during 25
years under a repressive government.
</P>
<P>
   He said she lied to FBI agents when they interviewed her last
summer at the Bank of New York because she had been conditioned in
the former Soviet Union to be guarded about anything she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''In that culture, you don't admit anything,'' Adler said.
</P>
<P>
   The judge agreed Kudryavtsev deserved a break.
</P>
<P>
   ''This sentence is sadder than many because I really don't have
any doubt that the defendant was manipulated and used and, if you
will, betrayed into the crimes,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
