<HEADLINE> Whitman announces $1 million grant to restore Ellis Island buildings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   JERSEY CITY, N.J. - Gov. Christie Whitman presented the National
Park Service with a ceremonial check Tuesday to mark a $1 million
donation from the state to restore buildings on Ellis Island.
</P>
<P>
   The state grant will be matched by federal funds, Whitman said
at a ceremony outside the island's immigration museum.
</P>
<P>
   ''This important reference point needs to be preserved so that
future generations can come, look and learn,'' Whitman said.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, many of the buildings that once housed hospitals
were deteriorated, Whitman said. Now state money has gone to
stabilize those structures so preservationist can begin work, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now is the time to redouble our efforts to save this historic
monument,'' Whitman said.
</P>
<P>
   The state also allocated $2.3 million last year for preservation
on the island.
</P>
<P>
   ''A million here, a million there, after a while you get real
money,'' joked Department of Environmental Commission Commissioner
Bob Shinn.
</P>
<P>
   A private group, Save Ellis Island!, hopes to preserve 30
buildings on the island's south side. The estimated cost is $6.6
million to begin preservation work.
</P>
<P>
   The group expects to get more matching funds from private
sources to aid the effort, said chairman Finn M.W. Caspersen.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now all we need to do is raise between $200 and $300 million
to save the island,'' Caspersen said.
</P>
</TEXT>
