<HEADLINE> Clemson Track Coach Agrees To Leave  </HEADLINE>
By PETE IACOBELLI
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEMSON, S.C. (AP) -- Clemson women's track coach Ralph White,
who was hired, unhired and hired again last year after a school
committee complained the job search was not extensive enough, has
agreed to leave the program after one season.
</P>
<P>
   ''I won the battle but lost the war,'' White said Tuesday. The
school's announcement called the move a mutual separation.
</P>
<P>
   White was hired twice within five weeks last summer. After his
first hiring June 18, the Status of Women commission wrote to
then-president Constantine ''Deno'' Curris complaining that no
women or minorities were considered.
</P>
<P>
   A search committee headed by associate athletic director Linda
White (no relation to Ralph) looked at about 50 applicants and
interviewed four candidates before Ralph White -- an assistant coach
for Clemson's men's team from 1997-99 -- was rehired.
</P>
<P>
   He had coached track and field at Allegheny (Pa.) College,
Southern Methodist, George Mason and Penn State before coming to
Clemson.
</P>
<P>
   White will be paid $46,344.82, what he was due for the final
year of his two-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   Distance runner Erika van Reenen said the coach was widely liked
by the athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's kind of a crazy situation,'' said van Reenen, who did not
want to discuss the circumstances of White's departure.
</P>
<P>
   Linda White again will head a search committee.
</P>
</TEXT>
