<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., Mexico Sign Antitrust Pact  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The United States and Mexico signed an
agreement Tuesday that would enable the two countries to cooperate
in antitrust enforcement, the Justice Department announced.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno said the agreement was ''an
important tool'' for consumer protection in both countries.
</P>
<P>
   Key provisions would encourage enforcement actions by each
nation at the other's request, and maintain confidentiality of
sensitive information provided by the other country.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement provides ''a sound basis for enhanced cooperation,
while minimizing possible conflicts between the two nations'
antitrust enforcement activities,'' said Joel I. Klein, assistant
attorney general in charge of antitrust.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has similar agreements with Brazil, Canada,
the European Union, Israel and Japan.
</P>
</TEXT>
