<HEADLINE> Hanged Teen's Kin, Reno To Meet  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The mother and brother of a black Mississippi
teen-ager found hanged will meet with lawmakers and Attorney
General Janet Reno on Wednesday, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Raynard Johnson, 17, was found hanging from a pecan tree a few
yards from the front door of his rural home June 16. Officials said
autopsy findings were consistent with suicide, but Johnson's family
questioned the ruling and called on the Rev. Jesse Jackson and
others to demand a federal investigation.
</P>
<P>
   His mother, Maria, and brother, Roger, will meet with Reno after
a news conference at the Capitol with Rep. John Conyers, D-Mich,
said Keenan Keller, Democratic counsel for the House Judiciary
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Conyers is the ranking Democrat on that committee.
</P>
<P>
   Keller also said it is possible the Johnsons might be invited
back to speak to the House Judiciary Committee at a later date.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI is conducting a preliminary probe into Johnson's death,
and state authorities say their investigations continue to be a
priority.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who spoke at the teen's funeral, also is expected to
escort the family to Washington. Jackson has been trying to focus
national attention on the death.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson has said he believes there are suspects in the case,
although officials have refused to confirm or deny that. He said
many things point to a racially motivated killing, including the
fact that Johnson and his brother had been friends with two
17-year-old white girls.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson has set up a $10,000 reward and toll-free tip line to
encourage more leads in the case.
</P>
</TEXT>
