<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House OK's 'Rosie the Riveter' Bill  </HEADLINE>
By BART JANSEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- ''Rosie the Riveter,'' the famous figure in a
poster whose flexed muscle embodied the fighting spirit of millions
of America's working women during World War II, is a step closer to
having a memorial.
</P>
<P>
   A bill that would establish the Rosie the Riveter/World War II
Home Front National Historic Park in Richmond, Calif., cleared the
House on a voice vote Tuesday. A Senate hearing on a similar
measure is scheduled Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The 'Rosie the Riveter' national park would salute the role of
the home front during World War II, particularly recognizing the
significant changes in the lives of women and minorities that
occurred during that era,'' said Rep. George Miller, D-Calif., who
sponsored the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ''We honor all of those who served in the war in uniform and in
coveralls, wearing helmets and bandannas, hoisting a machine gun or
a welder's torch.''
</P>
<P>
   Richmond was chosen for the park because it played a key role in
the domestic war effort. Its four shipyards employed 90,000 people
and produced 747 ships. Another 55 war-related industries in the
city employed 10,000, providing everything from uniforms to
vegetable oil. Women held one in four jobs in Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   A descendant of a real-life ''Rosie the Riveter'' welcomed the
recognition but said her mother's commitment during the war was not
extraordinary.
</P>
<P>
   ''Of that generation, most of the people didn't feel like they
did any more than they should have done. It sounds kind of corny,
but she did her part,'' said Vickie Jarvis of Clarksville, Ind.
</P>
<P>
   While the character on the poster was symbolic of all the women
in war work, Jarvis' late mother, Rose Will Monroe, was chosen to
portray ''Rosie'' in two movie clips used to sell war bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Monroe, a riveter at a Michigan bomber plant, fit the image of
the widely distributed poster, which featured a woman in bandanna
and overalls beneath the slogan, ''We can do it!''
</P>
<P>
   ''She just happened to be in the right place at the right
time,'' said Jarvis, who is assisting former Sen. Bob Dole's effort
to build a World War II memorial on the National Mall in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is H.R. 4063.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
