<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Appeals court rules that lower court judge can preside over case  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - A federal appeals court has ruled that a dispute
between the states of Connecticut and New York over whether non-New
York lobstermen can harvest New York water around Fishers Island
does not have to be decided by the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   The 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in a 2-to-1 decision
returned the dispute to U.S. District Judge Frederick J. Scullin
Jr.
</P>
<P>
   The judge had dismissed the case brought by Connecticut, saying
it had to be heard before the U.S. Supreme Court, which is supposed
to resolve controversies between two or more states.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court in a Friday ruling decided that the
Connecticut lawsuit could be decided at a lower court level in part
because New York state was not directly sued, only officials
including its commissioner of environmental conservation and the
Fishers Island Lobstermen's Association.
</P>
<P>
   ''This suit does not implicate a core aspect of New York's
sovereignty and seeks no relief that would require the state of New
York to disburse funds from its treasury to the state of
Connecticut,'' the appeals court wrote.
</P>
<P>
   In a dissent, Judge Sonia Sotomayor wrote that the case ''boils
down to one issue: whether Connecticut's suit is, in fact, a
controversy with New York. If so, it is subject to the Supreme
Court's exclusive jurisdiction.''
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut Attorney General Richard Blumenthal had originally
filed the lawsuit in U.S. District Court in Albany, challenging a
New York law which prohibits non-New York lobstermen from
harvesting in New York waters around Fishers Island, off the
eastern tip of Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit was trying to keep the area rich with lobsters open
for Connecticut's $30 million lobstering.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut fishermen take nearly 2.9 million pounds of lobster
each year, much of it from the Fisher's Island area. While the
island is on the New York side of the states' boundary, it lies
closer to Connecticut.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-11-00 1952 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000711.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Muslim Survivors Mark Anniversary  </HEADLINE>
By ALEXANDAR S. DRAGICEVIC
<TEXT>
<P>
   SREBRENICA, Bosnia-Herzegovina (AP) -- For five years, Kada
Hodzic has been recalling the moment when Serb soldiers snatched
her 18-year-old son from a crowd of refugees.
</P>
<P>
   She watched him walk away, called out to him, and finally,
quietly, wished him luck.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can still feel him,'' Hodzic said. ''I still believe he will
come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Hodzic, 42, and hundreds of other Muslim women who survived
Srebrenica chose to open old wounds Tuesday, traveling home with
2,000 other female survivors of the bloodiest massacre in Europe
since World War II. It is the first time Muslims could travel en
masse to Srebrenica, a region controlled by Bosnia's hard-line
Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Up to 8,000 Muslim men were believed killed when Serbs overran
the Muslim enclave of Srebrenica, just before the end of the
Bosnian war in 1995. Some 4,000 bodies have been recovered from
mass graves, and thousands are still missing.
</P>
<P>
   The massacre is regarded as the turning point of the Bosnian war
-- which led to Western military intervention.
</P>
<P>
   Even for this mission to pray in an enclave once designated a
U.N. safe area, Serb leaders insisted that the number of women be
kept low in exchange for guarantees of no trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ''They tell us we cannot live together again,'' Hodzic said.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs from Srebrenica deny anything unusual happened there,
and regarded Tuesday's ceremony as a provocation. They had declined
to guarantee the security of a convoy with 5,000 women traveling to
the site, but agreed after negotiations with U.N. officials that
2,000 could come.
</P>
<P>
   While the convoy passed through Bratunac, a town near
Srebrenica, several hundred Serbs raised three fingers -- a Serb
victory sign -- screamed insults and yelled, ''Get out of here!''
NATO-led peacekeepers and local police along the road prevented
serious attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Muslim survivors like Munira Subasic were angry at the
reception.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is difficult to go there, especially if we meet the people
who expelled us and who took our children away,'' Subasic said.
''They still walk around freely. Whenever we visit the town, we see
those faces again.''
</P>
<P>
   The women decided to go anyway, submitting to searches before
boarding 46 buses to cross into the Serb-held part of Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   At U.N. headquarters in New York, U.S. Ambassador Richard
Holbrooke, who negotiated the Dayton peace accords that ended the
Bosnian war, applauded all those who traveled to Srebrenica for the
commemoration in the face of ''outrageous threats'' by Serbs as
well as the few ''brave'' Muslim families who have resettled in the
city.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Serbs who are there must make room for them,'' Holbrooke
said.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke called for the ''butchers of Srebrenica'' to be
brought to justice, but also for reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   The Bosnian Muslim president, Alija Izetbegovic, his Bosnian
Croat colleague, Ante Jelavic and the U.S. Ambassador to Bosnia,
Thomas Miller, attended the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the Islamic Community in Bosnia, Mustafa Ceric, led
the prayers and declared that Bosnia's Muslims would keep searching
for justice.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a reminder,'' he said, ''that Srebrenica should never
be repeated again.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO helicopters and the U.S. Army patrolled near the boundary
line to help the women reach Potocari, a village near Srebrenica
where refugees sought shelter with Dutch U.N. troops after Serb
forces overran the city on July 11, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The Dutch could only watch, however, when soldiers loyal to
Bosnian Serb Gen. Ratko Mladic separated men from women and
children. The men were never seen again.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan acknowledged that the United
Nations' failure to help save thousands of Bosnian Muslims from a
Serb mass murder will forever haunt the world body.
</P>
<P>
   Annan said: ''We cannot undo this tragedy, but it is vitally
important that the right lessons be learned and applied in the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   Mladic and Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic have been
charged with war crimes in connection with the Srebrenica deaths.
They are still at large.
</P>
<P>
   Hodzic belongs to a group trying to win approval from
international officials to build a monument in Potocari. The Serbs
object to the location.
</P>
<P>
   Her group is angry that the international community did nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ''I ask myself: 'Couldn't this world do anything to prevent it?'
'' she said. ''Day and night -- especially at night.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
