<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prosecutors: Pataki team took bribes, but governor didn't know  </HEADLINE>
By TOM HAYS
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - A Republican fund-raiser teamed with a top
campaign aide to Gov. George Pataki to solicit bribes from parents
of violent felons on the promise their children would win parole,
prosecutors charged Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The fund-raiser, New Jersey businessman Yung Soo Yoo, ''decided
to put up for sale your state criminal justice system,'' Assistant
U.S. Attorney Margaret Giordano said during opening statements at
Yoo's campaign corruption trial in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   The case against Yoo - once valued by the likes of former U.S.
Sens. Alfonse D'Amato and Bob Dole as a deft fund-raiser in the
Korean-American community - stems from an ongoing federal
investigation into allegations of influence peddling by Pataki
aides. Yoo has denied any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   No one close to Pataki has been charged. But three parole
officials have been charged or convicted of lying to investigators,
and some of the governor's top aides have been called to testify
before a grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Giordano said in his opening statement that there is no evidence
the governor knew about the alleged scheme involving $36,000 in
contributions to ''Friends of Pataki'' in the mid-1990s. The
campaign aide linked to Yoo - Patrick Donahue - has not been
charged.
</P>
<P>
   But prosecutors allege Yoo and Donahue cut deals with three sets
of parents for Donahue to push for the release of their children
through a political ''pipeline'' connecting the governor's office
to the parole board. During one clandestine meeting, Donahue
promised an anxious mother, ''Give me three more months and I'll
make good,'' Giordano said.
</P>
<P>
   Giordano told the jury that a former parole official would
testify that two board members voted to release an armed robber and
gang member, John Kim, in 1996 after the official secretly informed
them: ''The governor's office wants this kid released.'' Records
show Kim's parents, who live in Queens, arranged for $7,000 in
contributions to the Pataki campaign, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney Nicholas DeFeis labeled the obstruction of
justice and political corruption charges against Yoo, 63, of Glen
Ridge, N.J., ''a fairy tale.''
</P>
<P>
   ''No one promised anyone their kids would get out of jail in
exchange for contributions,'' he said. ''That did not happen.''
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, Yoo faces up to 10 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in Albany on Tuesday, Gov. Pataki was asked
about the claims that Donahue might somehow be involved with Yoo's
case.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know what to say, other than anybody's entitled to
bring up anything. That's the nature of our process,'' Pataki said.
</P>
<P>
   Donahue's attorney did not immediately return a call seeking
comment.
</P>
<P>
   The parole investigation began after a man went to police in
1997 complaining that Yoo and Donahue failed to deliver on their
guarantee to free his son for $20,000 in donations.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, another parent, Incha Chung, testified Yoo assured
her a $10,000 contribution would buy freedom for her son once
Pataki was elected. She said the defendant was known as ''President
Yoo'' in Korean-American circles.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know something like that is possible in Korea,'' Chung
recalled saying to Yoo about the bribe. ''Is that do-able here?''
</P>
<P>
   ''Yes, it is possible in America by the governor's authority,''
she said Yoo replied.
</P>
<P>
   Chung's son is still serving time for attempted murder.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-11-00 2002 </TRAILER>
