<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 49ers' Bryant Young Honored by PFWA  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS (AP) -- San Francisco 49ers defensive tackle Bryant
Young, who made an inspiring comeback from a broken leg suffered
during the 1998 season, won the Halas Award from the Professional
Football Writers of America on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The award honors a player who overcame injury or adversity and
returned to excel on the field. Young was chosen over Dallas
Cowboys defensive tackle Alonzo Spellman and running back James
Stewart, then of the Jacksonville Jaguars.
</P>
<P>
   In other awards from the PFWA, New York Giants general manager
Ernie Accorsi won the Horrigan Award, the Tennessee Titans got the
Rozelle Award, and longtime Tampa Tribune columnist Tom McEwen
received the McCann Award.
</P>
<P>
   The Horrigan Award goes to a club or league official or player
for cooperation with the media. The Rozelle Award honors a league
public relations staff, while the McCann Award goes to a journalist
for long and meritorious work as a football writer.
</P>
</TEXT>
