<HEADLINE> Man arrested seven times on drunk driving charges arrested again  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WARWICK, N.Y. (AP) - A 34-year-old man was charged July 4 with
driving while intoxicated, his eighth drunk driving arrest in 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier on July 4, Warwick police had taken MacLeay's keys away
from him. Still, police accuse him of getting behind the wheel of a
car drunk.
</P>
<P>
   That arrest came a week after he pleaded guilty in Broome County
Court to charges stemming from a 1999 drunken driving arrest. He
was released on his own recognizance pending an August sentencing
date; he faces one to three years in prison, Broome County
Assistant District Attorney Rita Basile said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Does he have to kill someone before he gets it?'' asked Pat
Bodnar of Mothers Against Drunk Driving. ''I cannot believe this
person is still out there,'' she told the Middletown Times
Herald-Record.
</P>
<P>
   His criminal record includes two arrests 19 days apart in 1994
that led to a prison sentence of one to four years, according to
records. In all, he has done more than three years in state prison
and county jail, according to police and court records.
</P>
<P>
   ''You throw up your hands in frustration. State prison hasn't
done anything to help,'' Orange County District Attorney Frank
Phillips said. ''Most DWI offenders don't repeat. What allows the
system to work is the general obedience of the public to the
laws.''
</P>
<P>
   At his 1994 sentencing in Orange County Court, MacLeay said he
had sought treatment twice that year for alcoholism. He said he
suffered from cirrhosis of the liver.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am an alcoholic,'' he said. ''I'm trying, you know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
