<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Daughter helps rescue Mom when kayaks overturn  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   FRANKFORT, N.Y. (AP) - The morning after running the
15-kilometer Utica Boilermaker Road Race, Elizabeth Daly may have
run the race of her mother's life.
</P>
<P>
   Without shoes, Daly, 25, ran to the top of a steep bank on the
Mohawk River to signal for help. Her mother, Mary Ellen Daly, 55,
sat stranded and injured on a log in the rushing waters below after
both womens kayaks overturned.
</P>
<P>
   ''The rapids were very strong at that point. We both flipped
over, and my leg was squished between the kayak and a log,'' Mary
Ellen Daly told the Utica Observer-Dispatch after Monday's
accident.
</P>
<P>
   After freeing herself, Mary Ellen Daly waited on a log in the
river, because she felt it was too dangerous to cross the rivers
strong current with her injured leg.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities had a hard time finding her because of the high bank
and thick brush. In a small boat, two village of Frankfort firemen
found Mary Ellen Daly.
</P>
<P>
   ''When we saw her, she was sitting, clinging to an unstable log
in the rapids,'' said Philip Spaman, who said Daly was about 15
feet from the shore.
</P>
<P>
   Five police and fire departments from Herkimer County cut brush
with a small saw and axes and hoisted Mary Ellen Daly up the
20-foot bank in a basket.
</P>
<P>
   Her leg was treated for bruises.
</P>
<P>
   State spokesman Allen James said boaters should be aware that
waterways they have traveled before can change from year to year.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a different year with the rain weve had. The rapids we
have usually in May We may now have them,'' James said.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Ellen Daly said she learned a lesson from the mishap: never
go alone and make sure you have your life preserver on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-11-00 2033 </TRAILER>
