<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panel Seeks Drug Benefit Compromise  </HEADLINE>
By CURT ANDERSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- In an attempt to reach compromise on a
politically charged issue, the chairman of a key Senate panel is
drafting a Medicare prescription drug plan that would share costs
between the government and senior citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Finance Committee Chairman William Roth, R-Del., planned
to circulate the proposal Wednesday in hopes of reaching a middle
ground between President Clinton's large new government entitlement
plan and the House GOP's bill based on subsidized private
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic and Republican sources, speaking Tuesday night on
condition of anonymity, said that under Roth's emerging plan the
government would share prescription drug expenses with Medicare
recipients above a certain deductible amount. One deductible amount
being discussed was $500, but that was subject to change.
</P>
<P>
   Above the deductible, the sources said, the government would pay
half of all drug costs up to another level -- one preliminary figure
was $3,500 -- and as much as 80 percent the costs above that.
</P>
<P>
   This would appeal to GOP conservatives who want a co-payment in
order to hold down the program's size and cost.
</P>
<P>
   The plan would use benefit managers, much like health insurers
do, to buy drugs and design services at lowest possible cost. It
would also provide subsidies for low-income people to buy drugs.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Roth envisions changes to the current Medicare Part
A and Part B programs as they affect hospitalization. Under current
law, Medicare recipients must pay a $776 deductible per
hospitalization and a $100 deductible for services under Part B.
</P>
<P>
   The Roth proposal would combine both deductibles into one -- the
amount hasn't yet been decided -- and people on Medicare would get a
full 365 days of hospitalization with no other co-payment.
Currently, there is a tiered system of co-payments for
hospitalization and no coverage after 150 days.
</P>
<P>
   There are a myriad of other details to be ironed out, including
the proposal's cost. The GOP budget resolution calls for a
prescription drug benefit costing $40 billion over five years if
Medicare is also reformed, but Roth's plan could cost much more,
the sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the measure represents a glimmer of hope that compromise
could be reached despite the drug issue's potency as a campaign
issue. Clinton is adamantly against the House-passed private
insurance plan, and Republicans in Congress won't pass the
president's government-run plan costing $250 billion over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ''If it comes out of the Finance Committee in a bipartisan
fashion, it enhances the chances of something happening instead of
just statements by political parties,'' said Sen. John Breaux,
D-La.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-11-00 2035 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000711.0180 </DOCNO>
