<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dayne: Booster Same With Everyone  </HEADLINE>
By JR ROSS
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADISON, Wis. (AP) -- Heisman Trophy winner Ron Dayne didn't
think twice when a school booster offered him huge discounts at his
shoe store.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody he knew got the same deal.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you went to the store and you were nobody, he gave you a
discount,'' Dayne, now a member of the New York Giants, said
Tuesday. ''If you weren't even a football player, period, he gave
you a discount. That's just the way it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Dayne is one of 22 Wisconsin football and men's basketball
players identified in a report in the Wisconsin State Journal that
found they received discounts of 25 to 40 percent on purchases at
The Shoe Box and interest-free credit -- both possible NCAA rules
violations.
</P>
<P>
   The school also is probing allegations that some may have
exchanged university-issued shoes for merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   Association athletic director Vince Sweeney said players have
begun scheduling interviews with the school's compliance officer to
discuss their relationships with school booster Steve Schmitt, who
owns the store in Black Earth, about 20 miles west of Madison.
</P>
<P>
   He said the school hopes to make a report to the NCAA in several
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Among players listed in the report were Dayne, starting
quarterback Brooks Bollinger, and all five starters from the
basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts by The Associated Press to reach several players Tuesday
were unsuccessful, and school spokesman Steve Malchow said most
involved wanted to talk to investigators before addressing the
media.
</P>
<P>
   Schmitt denied he gave players any special treatment, a claim
Dayne backed up.
</P>
<P>
   Dayne said he never ran up a line of credit at the store or
received any special treatment. He said he paid off his bills after
each visit or his uncle Rob Reid did it for him.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you'd go back to the store, you'd pay it whenever you had
the money,'' Dayne said. ''Usually, he'd give you a little time
limit.''
</P>
<P>
   Football coach Barry Alvarez, speaking Tuesday before a charity
golf event at the Greater Milwaukee Open, reiterated the
university's position that his players had no idea they were
receiving any discounts not available to the public.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel really confident that my players didn't intentionally
break any rules,'' Alvarez said. ''I think they honestly felt they
were getting the same price anyone would.''
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez said he hasn't been to The Shoe Box for at least six
years, but he was aware of the store's reputation for discounts. He
said his players are educated on possible NCAA violations, and any
rumors of abuses would have been investigated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-11-00 2052 </TRAILER>
