<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jury seated in trial over Disney sports complex  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) - A jury was seated Tuesday in a civil case
pitting the Walt Disney Co. against a New York businessman who is
accusing the company of stealing his idea for the Wide World of
Sports Complex.
</P>
<P>
   A jury of three men and three women were seated for the trial,
which is expected to last four weeks. Opening arguments were
scheduled for Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Among those on the witness list were several top Disney
executives, including chairman and CEO Michael Eisner.
</P>
<P>
   However, Disney attorneys and the plaintiffs' lawyers, including
Johnnie Cochran Jr., were holding mediation talks late Tuesday that
could put off a trial.
</P>
<P>
   Plaintiffs Nicholas Stracick, of Buffalo, N.Y., and Edward
Russell, of Fonthill, Ontario, claim Disney used their ''trade
secrets'' to develop the sports complex after they invested more
than $100,000 and three years designing the project.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, which seeks more than $1 billion in damages,
accuses Disney of theft, breach of contract, misappropriation of
trade secrets and fraud.
</P>
<P>
   ''The ideas he had were taken and appropriated by this giant,''
Cochran said. ''It's substantial ... They're making lot of money
off this idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Disney says the plaintiffs' idea was not unique and that it had
been planning a sports complex years before Stracick pitched his
idea.
</P>
<P>
   ''The world is full of Mr. Stracick's idea,'' Disney attorney
David Evans said. ''He doesn't own the idea. The notion of putting
together sports facilities with athletic events has been around
since the days of the ancient Greeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Stracick, a former professional baseball umpire, teamed with
Russell in the late 1980s to form a Tampa-based company called All
Pro Sports Camps Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The two men presented their idea to Disney officials in
September 1986, submitting a written proposal for a multi-sport
theme park based at Walt Disney World, according to the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Disney officials expressed interest in the concept and
even talked about forming a joint venture with All Pro, according
to the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   During the next three years, the two sides met 50 times and
exchanged more than 500 phone calls, said Willie Gary, co-counsel
for the plaintiffs. All Pro invested more than $100,000 in a scale
model of the sports complex, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Disney opened its Wide World of Sports complex in 1997, the same
year the lawsuit was filed.
</P>
<P>
   Evans said Disney had plans to develop similar sporting
facilities dating back to the 1960s. Disney used its own architects
and sports experts to design and develop the complex, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The complex hosts a variety of professional and amateur sporting
events, including spring training for the Atlanta Braves.
</P>
<P>
   ''They stole the concept of the all pro sports complex,'' said
Stracick, 65. ''We're finally getting our day in court.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-11-00 2114 </TRAILER>
