<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shot Doctor Stabbed in Canada  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) -- A doctor who was once shot by
a suspected anti-abortion activist was wounded in his office
Tuesday by a knife-wielding attacker, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   A hooded assailant stabbed abortion provider Garson Romalis once
in his lower back, but the wound was not life-threatening.
</P>
<P>
   The assailant escaped and no suspects had been arrested as of
late Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Police said they didn't know of a motive for the attack but
indicated it might have been linked to Romalis's practice, warning
other doctors who perform abortions in the Vancouver area to be
careful.
</P>
<P>
   ''It would appear that this doctor was targeted,'' said
Vancouver police Constable Anne Drennan. ''We ask that all other
abortion services providers go on high alert.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the doctor first believed he had been punched. He began
to follow the attacker before realizing he was bleeding and sought
help.
</P>
<P>
   She described the suspect a man about 20 years old with a dark
complexion.
</P>
<P>
   Police refused to identify Romalis as the victim, but office
workers in the building confirmed his identity.
</P>
<P>
   ''My heart goes out to Mr. Romalis's family,'' said Attorney
General Andrew Petter.
</P>
<P>
   Romalis, who was shot in the leg at his home in 1994, was the
first of five doctors in Canada and the northeastern United States
to be hit by sniper's bullets over the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   Barnett Slepian of Amherst, N.Y., was the only fatality. He was
killed in 1998 by a bullet fired through his kitchen window.
</P>
<P>
   The other three were shot in Buffalo, N.Y., Winnipeg, Manitoba,
and Ancaster, Ontario.
</P>
<P>
   James Kopp, an American anti-abortion activist, was charged in
the Slepian killing but remains at large. The FBI has said there is
little doubt the same man pulled the trigger in each attack.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides in the abortion debate reacted to Tuesday's stabbing
with horror.
</P>
<P>
   ''Here we have an abortion doctor being targeted in the most
vile, violent way by a fanatic and it's extremely upsetting,'' said
Joyce Arthur, a spokeswoman for the Pro-Choice Action Network.
</P>
<P>
   ''Anyone who does this is not part of the pro-life movement,''
said Monica Roddis, executive director of Pro-Life Society of
British Columbia. We absolutely disassociate ourselves entirely
from anyone who does this kind of thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
