<DOCNO> APW20000711.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> All-Star Game Tied After 3 Innings  </HEADLINE>
By RONALD BLUM
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- Chipper Jones became only the third player in 31
years to homer during in an All-Star game in his home ballpark,
leaving the National and American leagues tied 1-1 after three
innings Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   After Kevin Brown put the NL ahead with a bases-loaded walk to
Carl Everett in the top of the third, Jones connected for an
opposite-field homer to left-center in the bottom half, earning a
huge ovation from the Atlanta Braves' fans at Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   Hank Aaron, the former Brave who threw out the first pitch
Tuesday night, homered in 1972 at Atlanta-Fulton County Stadium,
which stood adjacent to Turner Field and is now a parking lot.
Sandy Alomar Jr. homered for Cleveland three years ago at Jacobs
Field. In all, Jones became the 10th player to accomplish the feat.
</P>
<P>
   In the first two innings, pitching dominated, with David Wells
holding the NL to two hits, while Randy Johnson and Danny Graves
allowed one hit each to the AL.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who walked just 27 in 125 innings during the first half
of the season, walked three in his inning, throwing 33 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Roberto Alomar walked with one out and Derek Jeter singled.
Yankees teammate Bernie Williams hit a fielder's choice-grounder to
third and Oakland's Jason Giambi walked, loading the bases.
</P>
<P>
   Brown then fell behind Everett 3-0 in the count and threw a pair
of pitches that Everett missed. After a foul, Everett took a high
pitch for ball four.
</P>
<P>
   Ivan Rodriguez then flied out, ending the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Jones' homer, which came on a 2-0 pitch, was his first in
All-Star play.
</P>
<P>
   Missing seven of the 16 starters elected by fans last week, the
All-Star game began on a muggy night with less anticipation that
usual.
</P>
<P>
   Mark McGwire, Ken Griffey Jr., Mike Piazza and Barry Bonds were
missing from the National League lineup, while Cal Ripken, Alex
Rodriguez and Manny Ramirez were injured in the American League.
</P>
<P>
   And Pedro Martinez, who struck out five batters in the first two
innings of last year's game at Fenway Park, also was out.
</P>
<P>
   With a temperature of 86 degrees and humidity at 72 percent when
the first pitch was thrown at 8:45 p.m., a sellout crowd at Turner
Field got to see a new twist: the All-Stars taking their children
on the field with them during pregame introductions. Some of the
kids hit the field when four F-14 fighter jets roared over the
ballpark following the national anthems.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta first baseman Andres Galarraga got the biggest cheer, a
30-second standing ovation. After missing all of 1999 while
battling cancer, Galarraga returned this season and hit .294 in the
first half with 20 homers and 62 RBIs, earning an All-Star berth.
</P>
<P>
   Among those watching from the commissioner's box next to the NL
dugout was former President Jimmy Carter; Time Warner vice chairman
Ted Turner; Frank Torre, brother of AL manager Joe Torre; and
former commissioner Fay Vincent, who was ousted by owners in 1992.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
