<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-11 23:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Doctor Charged With Murder  </HEADLINE>
By FRANK ELTMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   GARDEN CITY, N.Y. (AP) -- A former doctor suspected of poisoning
patients from Ohio to Zimbabwe was charged Tuesday with the 1993
murder of three patients at a veterans hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors announced the new charges against Michael
Swango, 45, just days before he was to be released from a Colorado
prison, where he is serving a 42-month sentence for lying on an
application for a residency at Stony Brook University Medical
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Swango failed to disclose that he had spent 30 months in jail
and lost his medical license in 1985 for poisoning six co-workers
in Quincy, Ill. Prosecutors had brought charges against him in part
to buy them time to build the murder case.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors suspect that soon after graduating from Southern
Illinois University Medical School in 1983, Swango poisoned
patients and co-workers in the United States and abroad for more
than a decade. None of the people died.
</P>
<P>
   But after Swango was hired by Stony Brook, three patients died
in his care at the Veterans Administration Hospital in Garden City,
Long Island, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   Swango is suspected of killing all three patients by injecting
them with toxins. In two of the cases, he is accused of falsely
telling associates that the patients' families had issued ''do not
resuscitate'' orders.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors also believe a fourth patient was poisoned, but
there wasn't enough evidence to prove the injection led to death.
Swango is charged with assault in that case.
</P>
<P>
   Swango's court-appointed lawyer, Randi Chavis, did not
immediately return a call seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   When Swango left Stony Brook, he headed for Zimbabwe, where he
was hired by the Zimbabwe Association of Church Hospitals in 1994,
according to Tuesday's 17-page indictment. About a year later,
patients at hospitals there began showing signs of poisoning.
</P>
<P>
   Swango was suspended from practice at the Mnene Mission Hospital
in Zimbabwe in July 1995. Prosecutors there are still investigating
and cooperated with U.S. prosecutors in preparing Tuesday's
indictment, Lynch said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
