<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US, N.Korea Missile Talks Nears End  </HEADLINE>
By RANJAN ROY
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) -- Amid new hopes of progress, U.S.
and North Korean negotiators went into their final meeting
Wednesday in three days of talks on Pyongyang's development and
export of missiles.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations follow new willingness by long-reclusive North
Korea to discuss defense issues and the latest failed test for a
U.S. missile defense system aimed at stopping strikes from North
Korea and other so-called countries of concern.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Myong Gil, a North Korean negotiator, told reporters after
Tuesday's talks that ''the atmosphere was very sincere'' and the
chief topics were missile exports and compensation to North Korea.
An agreement was ''under negotiation.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States wants North Korea to halt the development and
export of ballistic missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Pyongyang has said it will not negotiate on its sovereign right
to develop defensive missiles. There are hopes it may be more
flexible on its exports, though they are a vital source of hard
currency.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea has in the past reportedly demanded annual
compensation of $1 billion for three years if it curbs missile
exports.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, chief U.S. negotiator, Robert Einhorn, had greeted
North Korean delegates with handshakes and smiles after saying the
United States was prepared to move toward fundamentally improved
relations.
</P>
<P>
   The United States claims North Korea is the world's top exporter
of missile equipment and technology, selling to such countries as
Pakistan and Iran.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-1998, Pyongyang rattled Asia by test-firing a missile
over Japan into the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the difficulties, Einhorn said Monday that the talks
were being held in a positive atmosphere, largely due to a June
summit between North Korean leader Kim Jong Il and South Korean
President Kim Dae-Jung.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea also recently agreed to a moratorium on tests of
long-range missiles in exchange for an easing of U.S. sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   It has opened official talks with Japan, moved to establish
diplomatic relations with many countries in Asia and Europe, and
joined a security forum of Southeast Asian nations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
